C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\r2_manuscript_changes.md:231:> We theorize that diversity-related descriptive feedback about selection decisions (e.g., the racial or gender composition of those selected for past opportunities) can be effective at promoting diversification in subsequent selection decisions even in the absence of an explicit goal or norm when it suggests past choices have lacked diversity. We further posit that such feedback can be more effective at influencing future choices than descriptive feedback about other features of selection decisions. Why? Because diversity-related feedback can draw attention to the potential reputational and self-image ramifications of choices even in the absence of an explicit goal. Specifically, we propose that when such feedback highlights the underrepresentation of women or racial minorities in past selections, it will raise concerns that past behavior could be seen as discriminatory and therefore risk rebuke. This is a reaction referred to as "motivation to respond without prejudice" (Plant & Devine, 1998), and it is driven by people's desire to (1) avoid negative repercussions from others (i.e., to protect their reputation; Leary & Kowalski, 1990; Lerner & Tetlock, 1999) and (2) maintain a positive self-view or self-image (Plant & Devine, 1998, 2009; Crandall & Eshleman, 2003; Apfelbaum et al., 2008).
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\r2_manuscript_changes.md:236:> We theorize that diversity-related descriptive feedback about selection decisions (e.g., the racial or gender composition of those selected for past opportunities) can be effective at promoting diversification in subsequent selection decisions even in the absence of an explicit goal or norm when it suggests past choices have lacked diversity. We further posit that such feedback can be more effective at influencing future choices than descriptive feedback about other features of selection decisions. [This prediction does not assume that participants' initial selections reflect a normatively "appropriate" or correct level for any attribute. Instead, we predict that descriptive feedback shifts subsequent selections on dimensions that carry an implicit injunctive norm the feedback calls into question, which we argue is true of race and gender but not of the comparison attributes we test.] Why? Because diversity-related feedback can draw attention to the potential reputational and self-image ramifications of choices even in the absence of an explicit goal. Specifically, we propose that when such feedback highlights the underrepresentation of women or racial minorities in past selections, it will raise concerns that past behavior could be seen as discriminatory and therefore risk rebuke. This is a reaction referred to as "motivation to respond without prejudice" (Plant & Devine, 1998), and it is driven by people's desire to (1) avoid negative repercussions from others (i.e., to protect their reputation; Leary & Kowalski, 1990; Lerner & Tetlock, 1999) and (2) maintain a positive self-view or self-image (Plant & Devine, 1998, 2009; Crandall & Eshleman, 2003; Apfelbaum et al., 2008).
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\_footnotes_dump.txt:69:To address the possibility that comparison-attribute feedback has weaker effects simply because participants are already using these attributes appropriately in their initial selections, we conducted a cross-study analysis pooling Studies 2, 3A, 3B, and 4B and restricting attention to participants whose initial selections contained zero of a given attribute. Among this conservative subset, where appropriate prior use cannot account for any non-response to feedback, race or gender feedback raised the likelihood of selecting a woman or racial by 22.50 percentage points (Woman: +27.59 pp; Racial Minority: +9.77; p < .001, N = 864)., whereas comparison-attribute feedback shifted subsequent selections by only +7.25 percentage points (p = .19, N = 414); a Wald test confirms the difference between the two pooled coefficients is significant (p = .016). Full per-cell results are reported in Appendix Section S[X].

