C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_final_audit.session.log:802:[codex] 406:Notes: Each row reports the percentage-point increase in the likelihood that a participant's final selection had a given attribute, induced by random assignment to receive descriptive feedback about that attribute in the participant's set of initial selections, estimated via ordinary-least-squares regression with HC3 robust standard errors. Identity-target feedback estimates correspond to Model 1 of the per-study regression tables in the manuscript and Appendix (Tables 3, S3, S5, S7, and S9); comparison-attribute feedback estimates correspond to the analogous single-equation specification with the comparison attribute as both the outcome and the feedback target. The right-most column reports the p-value of the Wald F-test of equality between the identity-target and comparison-attribute feedback effects, estimated from a Zellner (1962) seemingly-unrelated regression system pairing the identity equation with each comparison equation; rejection indicates that the identity-target feedback effect is significantly larger in magnitude than the corresponding comparison-attribute feedback effect. For Study 2, the Zellner system was not pre-registered (because of the smaller sample), and the reported Wald p-values are estimated post-hoc using the same SUR specification applied to Studies 3AΓÇô4B. Comparison attributes were chosen to be domain-relevant for each selection task; in Study 4B, the comparison attributes were additionally pre-tested for importance and confirmed to be rated at least as important as the identity-target attribute. Study 1 is excluded because participants did not generate their own initial selections (the initial portfolio was stimulus-sampled), and Study 5 is excluded because its design varies the initial candidate pool's composition rather than holding it constant. + p < .10; * p < .05; ** p < .01; *** p < .001.
