C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_final_audit.session.log:928:[codex] 43:Prior to data collection, we ran a pre-registered pretest (https://aspredicted.org/xa7u94.pdf; N = 300 Prolific participants) to compare the rated importance of the four attributes featured in Study 1 for selecting NPR experts. Each participant was randomly assigned to rate one attribute on a scale from 1 (ΓÇ£Not at all importantΓÇ¥) to 7 (ΓÇ£Very importantΓÇ¥). Compared to gender (ΓÇ£were womenΓÇ¥: M = 3.87, SD = 1.92, n = 75), participants rated ΓÇ£worked at a universityΓÇ¥ as significantly more important (M = 4.50, SD = 1.48, n = 74; t(139.0) = 2.26, p = .026, d = 0.37) and ΓÇ£were under 50 years oldΓÇ¥ as similarly important (M = 4.05, SD = 1.74, n = 75; t(146.6) = 0.62, p = .534, d = 0.10). ΓÇ£Were based on the West Coast of the United StatesΓÇ¥ was rated as less important than gender (M = 3.11, SD = 1.81, n = 74; t(146.7) = 2.48, p = .014, d = 0.41; full results in Appendix Section S[X]). Two of the three comparison attributes were thus rated as at least as important as gender. These results suggest that differences in the perceived importance of the type of feedback participants receive about their selections in Study 1 are unlikely to account for why only feedback about gender moved subsequent selections.
