C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_final_audit.session.log:1011:[codex] 168-        	Across seven pre-registered experiments, including a framed field study in a real organization, we investigate the impact of providing descriptive feedback about the gender and racial diversity of past candidate selections on evaluatorsΓÇÖ future choices. In Studies 1-5 we demonstrate that when women (or racial minorities) are underrepresented in candidate pools, giving participants feedback about the fraction of women (or racial minorities) they initially select increases the likelihood that they will subsequently choose to add a woman (or racial minority) to their portfolio. By contrast, when participants receive descriptive feedback about the fraction of selectees with other domain-relevant attributes that are DEI-irrelevant (e.g., the fraction of Technologists on a panel instead of the fraction of women on that panel), it does not have the same impact on their subsequent selections (i.e., they are less likely to subsequently select a Technologist). In Studies 4A and 4B, we identify peopleΓÇÖs motivation to respond without prejudice as a key mechanism underlying the effect of descriptive feedback on peopleΓÇÖs subsequent DEI-related selection decisions. We find that both internal and external motivation to respond without prejudice mediates the relationship between receiving descriptive feedback about past selectees and making more gender-or-racially-diverse future candidate selections. 
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_final_audit.session.log:1039:[codex] 14:We theorize that diversity-related descriptive feedback about selection decisions (e.g., the racial or gender composition of those selected for past opportunities) can be effective at promoting diversification in subsequent selection decisions even in the absence of an explicit goal or norm when it suggests past choices have lacked diversity. We further posit that such feedback can be more effective at influencing future choices than descriptive feedback about other features of selection decisions. Why? Because diversity-related feedback can draw attention to the potential reputational and self-image ramifications of choices even in the absence of an explicit goal. Specifically, we propose that when such feedback highlights the underrepresentation of women or racial minorities in past selections, it will raise concerns that past behavior could be seen as discriminatory and therefore risk rebuke. This is a reaction referred to as ΓÇ£motivation to respond without prejudiceΓÇ¥ (Plant & Devine, 1998), and it is driven by peopleΓÇÖs desire to (1) avoid negative repercussions from others (i.e., to protect their reputation; Leary & Kowalski, 1990; Lerner & Tetlock, 1999) and (2) maintain a positive self-view or self-image (Plant & Devine, 1998, 2009; Crandall & Eshleman, 2003; Apfelbaum et al., 2008). 
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_final_audit.session.log:1057:[codex] 108:Internal motivation to respond without prejudice. To assess internal motives (e.g., image concerns) in the final author selection, we adapted four items from Plant and DevineΓÇÖs (1998) internal motivation to respond without prejudice scale (e.g., ΓÇ£Given my personal values and beliefs, an important factor in my selection of the seventh author to add to my list was my desire to promote the success of racial minorities.ΓÇ¥; CronbachΓÇÖs ╬▒ = 0.93). Items used a  1 (Strongly disagree) to 7 (Strongly agree) scale and, as pre-registered, were separately z-scored and then averaged.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_final_audit.session.log:1058:[codex] 109:External motivation to respond without prejudice. To assess external motives (e.g., reputational concerns) in the final author selection,  we adapted three items from Plant and DevineΓÇÖs external motivation to respond without prejudice scale (e.g., ΓÇ£When making my decision about who to select as my seventh author, I considered the social pressures I face to appear to promote racial minorities where they are typically underrepresented.ΓÇ¥; CronbachΓÇÖs ╬▒ = 0.90). Items used a 1 (Strongly disagree) to 7 (Strongly agree) scale, and as pre-registered, were separately z-scored and then averaged. 
