C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_final_audit.session.log:1120:[codex] 171:Our work makes two primary theoretical contributions. First, we offer new insights about how and when descriptive feedback motivates behavior change. According to Feedback Intervention Theory, feedback is most effective when paired with explicit goals, standards, or explicit injunctive norms that signal a clear gap between current performance and a desired state (Kluger & DeNisi, 1996; Locke & Latham, 2019; Schultz et al., 2007; Schultz et al., 2018). Purely descriptive feedback is often viewed as insufficient to drive change because it lacks a directive. We show that descriptive feedback can consistently motivate behavior change in the absence of explicit prescriptions. When such feedback targets DEI-relevant attributes of past selections and suggests women or minorities have been overlooked, the feedback itself activates two distinct motivations to respond without prejudice (Plant & Devine, 1998): an internal motivation, rooted in a decision maker's own egalitarian commitments and desire to view themselves as non-prejudiced, and an external motivation, rooted in concern about how their selections will be judged by others.the feedback itself elicits reputational or self-image concerns ΓÇô specifically, internal and external motivation to respond without prejudice. In the context of diversity, an explicit goal, target, social norm or injunctive norm does not need to be coupled with feedback to induce a response because an implicit injunctive norm to avoid prejudice has already been internalized by the decision-maker. This suggests that the utility of providing descriptive feedback absent an explicit goal, target or norm lies in its ability to focus attention on past behavior in arenas where individuals already harbor self-image or reputational concerns.
