C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_final_audit.session.log:1958:[codex] 406:Notes: Each row reports the percentage-point increase in the likelihood that a participant's final selection had a given attribute, induced by random assignment to receive descriptive feedback about that attribute in the participant's set of initial selections, estimated via ordinary-least-squares regression with HC3 robust standard errors. Identity-target feedback estimates correspond to Model 1 of the per-study regression tables in the manuscript and Appendix (Tables 3, S3, S5, S7, and S9); comparison-attribute feedback estimates correspond to the analogous single-equation specification with the comparison attribute as both the outcome and the feedback target. The right-most column reports the p-value of the Wald F-test of equality between the identity-target and comparison-attribute feedback effects, estimated from a Zellner (1962) seemingly-unrelated regression system pairing the identity equation with each comparison equation; rejection indicates that the identity-target feedback effect is significantly larger in magnitude than the corresponding comparison-attribute feedback effect. For Study 2, the Zellner system was not pre-registered (because of the smaller sample), and the reported Wald p-values are estimated post-hoc using the same SUR specification applied to Studies 3AΓÇô4B. Comparison attributes were chosen to be domain-relevant for each selection task; in Study 4B, the comparison attributes were additionally pre-tested for importance and confirmed to be rated at least as important as the identity-target attribute. Study 1 is excluded because participants did not generate their own initial selections (the initial portfolio was stimulus-sampled), and Study 5 is excluded because its design varies the initial candidate pool's composition rather than holding it constant. + p < .10; * p < .05; ** p < .01; *** p < .001.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_final_audit.session.log:1988:[codex] manuscript_gdoc_text.txt:29:We present seven pre-registered experiments (total N = 6,502), including one framed field experiment (Harrison & List, 2004), to examine how descriptive feedback about a portfolio of past choices affects subsequent selection decisions. In most of our studies, we employ a candidate selection paradigm illustrated in Figure 1. Participants begin by choosing a portfolio of six to seven candidates (e.g., panelists, authors) from a larger candidate pool including twenty-four to twenty-six options (in Study 1, participants are simply told to imagine they have made prior selections and informed about the composition of those prior selections). After making their initial selections (or being told about them in Study 1), participants are randomly assigned to receive two to three pieces of descriptive feedback summarizing the characteristics of their initial selectees. Participants assigned to a treatment condition receive feedback summarizing either the gender (Studies 1, 3B, 4B and 5) or racial (Studies 3A and 4A) composition of their initially selected candidates (e.g., the percentage who were female; the percentage who were racial minorities) alongside one or two pieces of additional descriptive feedback about their initially selected candidates to both (1) obfuscate the purpose of the research and (2) measure the impact of such feedback focused on non-DEI-related characteristics of past selectees (e.g., the percentage of prior selectees who were CEOs; the percentage who were genre-spanning writers). Participants assigned to the control condition also receive descriptive feedback about their initially selected candidates (e.g., the percentage who were technologists; the percentage who were born in the 1800s), but this feedback never references the race or gender composition of prior selectees. Finally, participants are given the opportunity to select one or more additional candidates to add to the group (e.g., of panelists or authors) that they just created. Our outcomes of interest are the attributes of these subsequent selecteesΓÇöand in particular, their gender (in Studies 1, 3B, 4B and 5) or race (in Studies 3A and 4A). Data for Studies 1ΓÇô5 as well as analysis code for all studies can be found on OSF: https://osf.io/zxyw2/.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_final_audit.session.log:1992:[codex] manuscript_gdoc_text.txt:171:Our work makes two primary theoretical contributions. First, we offer new insights about how and when descriptive feedback motivates behavior change. According to Feedback Intervention Theory, feedback is most effective when paired with explicit goals, standards, or explicit injunctive norms that signal a clear gap between current performance and a desired state (Kluger & DeNisi, 1996; Locke & Latham, 2019; Schultz et al., 2007; Schultz et al., 2018). Purely descriptive feedback is often viewed as insufficient to drive change because it lacks a directive. We show that descriptive feedback can consistently motivate behavior change in the absence of explicit prescriptions. When such feedback targets DEI-relevant attributes of past selections and suggests women or minorities have been overlooked, the feedback itself activates two distinct motivations to respond without prejudice (Plant & Devine, 1998): an internal motivation, rooted in a decision maker's own egalitarian commitments and desire to view themselves as non-prejudiced, and an external motivation, rooted in concern about how their selections will be judged by others.the feedback itself elicits reputational or self-image concerns ΓÇô specifically, internal and external motivation to respond without prejudice. In the context of diversity, an explicit goal, target, social norm or injunctive norm does not need to be coupled with feedback to induce a response because an implicit injunctive norm to avoid prejudice has already been internalized by the decision-maker. This suggests that the utility of providing descriptive feedback absent an explicit goal, target or norm lies in its ability to focus attention on past behavior in arenas where individuals already harbor self-image or reputational concerns.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_final_audit.session.log:1993:[codex] manuscript_gdoc_text.txt:173:We also contribute to the literature on social norms. Past research demonstrates that people are strongly motivated to conform to the norms of their culture (Cialdini et al., 1990). We show that descriptive feedback alone can activate concerns about existing, implicit injunctive societal normsΓÇöspecifically norms regarding diversity and against discrimination (Barr et al., 2018)ΓÇöwithout the need for an explicit command or ΓÇ£injunctiveΓÇ¥ message. Thus, we show that descriptive feedback can be a tool for activating greater attention to unspoken and therefore implicit injunctive norms.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_final_audit.session.log:2049:[codex] manuscript_gdoc_text.txt:406:Notes: Each row reports the percentage-point increase in the likelihood that a participant's final selection had a given attribute, induced by random assignment to receive descriptive feedback about that attribute in the participant's set of initial selections, estimated via ordinary-least-squares regression with HC3 robust standard errors. Identity-target feedback estimates correspond to Model 1 of the per-study regression tables in the manuscript and Appendix (Tables 3, S3, S5, S7, and S9); comparison-attribute feedback estimates correspond to the analogous single-equation specification with the comparison attribute as both the outcome and the feedback target. The right-most column reports the p-value of the Wald F-test of equality between the identity-target and comparison-attribute feedback effects, estimated from a Zellner (1962) seemingly-unrelated regression system pairing the identity equation with each comparison equation; rejection indicates that the identity-target feedback effect is significantly larger in magnitude than the corresponding comparison-attribute feedback effect. For Study 2, the Zellner system was not pre-registered (because of the smaller sample), and the reported Wald p-values are estimated post-hoc using the same SUR specification applied to Studies 3AΓÇô4B. Comparison attributes were chosen to be domain-relevant for each selection task; in Study 4B, the comparison attributes were additionally pre-tested for importance and confirmed to be rated at least as important as the identity-target attribute. Study 1 is excluded because participants did not generate their own initial selections (the initial portfolio was stimulus-sampled), and Study 5 is excluded because its design varies the initial candidate pool's composition rather than holding it constant. + p < .10; * p < .05; ** p < .01; *** p < .001.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_session.log:88:[codex] existing closing sentence about "focus attention on past behavior". The new paragraph
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_session.log:294:[codex] Many organizations provide employees feedback on the demographics of whom theyΓÇÖve chosen to spotlight, hire, and promote, hoping to spur more diverse selections. However, it is an open question whether providing purely descriptive feedback can improve diversity. We theorized and showed that descriptive feedback highlighting low past selection rates of women or racial minorities (e.g., 5% of previous experts you interviewed were women) triggers a motivation to respond without prejudice, increasing the subsequent selection of members of underrepresented groups. Conversely, providing descriptive feedback about low selection rates of other attributes (e.g., areas of expertise, recent release dates) that doesnΓÇÖt evoke image or reputational concerns has less influence on future decisions. We demonstrated these patterns across seven pre-registered experiments (total N=6,502), including one framed field experiment (Study 2). In Study 4, we identified motivation to respond without prejudice as a mediator of the effect of descriptive feedback about past choices on future selections of women and racial minorities. Moreover, in Study 5 we showed that when women are overrepresented, the effect of descriptive feedback reverses in direction, increasing the subsequent selection of men (due to concerns about fairness), but this effect is significantly smaller in magnitude than the standard effect produced when women are underrepresented. Practically, the effects of descriptive feedback were 45-80% as large as imposing a strict quota requiring that at least one woman or racial minority be selected for a given opportunity, highlighting that descriptive feedback is a light-touch but potentially powerful intervention for shifting inclusive behaviors. 
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_session.log:304:[codex] We theorize that diversity-related descriptive feedback about selection decisions (e.g., the racial or gender composition of those selected for past opportunities) can be effective at promoting diversification in subsequent selection decisions even in the absence of an explicit goal or norm when it suggests past choices have lacked diversity. We further posit that such feedback can be more effective at influencing future choices than descriptive feedback about other features of selection decisions. Why? Because diversity-related feedback can draw attention to the potential reputational and self-image ramifications of choices even in the absence of an explicit goal. Specifically, we propose that when such feedback highlights the underrepresentation of women or racial minorities in past selections, it will raise concerns that past behavior could be seen as discriminatory and therefore risk rebuke. This is a reaction referred to as ΓÇ£motivation to respond without prejudiceΓÇ¥ (Plant & Devine, 1998), and it is driven by peopleΓÇÖs desire to (1) avoid negative repercussions from others (i.e., to protect their reputation; Leary & Kowalski, 1990; Lerner & Tetlock, 1999) and (2) maintain a positive self-view or self-image (Plant & Devine, 1998, 2009; Crandall & Eshleman, 2003; Apfelbaum et al., 2008). 
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_session.log:319:[codex] We present seven pre-registered experiments (total N = 6,502), including one framed field experiment (Harrison & List, 2004), to examine how descriptive feedback about a portfolio of past choices affects subsequent selection decisions. In most of our studies, we employ a candidate selection paradigm illustrated in Figure 1. Participants begin by choosing a portfolio of six to seven candidates (e.g., panelists, authors) from a larger candidate pool including twenty-four to twenty-six options (in Study 1, participants are simply told to imagine they have made prior selections and informed about the composition of those prior selections). After making their initial selections (or being told about them in Study 1), participants are randomly assigned to receive two to three pieces of descriptive feedback summarizing the characteristics of their initial selectees. Participants assigned to a treatment condition receive feedback summarizing either the gender (Studies 1, 3B, 4B and 5) or racial (Studies 3A and 4A) composition of their initially selected candidates (e.g., the percentage who were female; the percentage who were racial minorities) alongside one or two pieces of additional descriptive feedback about their initially selected candidates to both (1) obfuscate the purpose of the research and (2) measure the impact of such feedback focused on non-DEI-related characteristics of past selectees (e.g., the percentage of prior selectees who were CEOs; the percentage who were genre-spanning writers). Participants assigned to the control condition also receive descriptive feedback about their initially selected candidates (e.g., the percentage who were technologists; the percentage who were born in the 1800s), but this feedback never references the race or gender composition of prior selectees. Finally, participants are given the opportunity to select one or more additional candidates to add to the group (e.g., of panelists or authors) that they just created. Our outcomes of interest are the attributes of these subsequent selecteesΓÇöand in particular, their gender (in Studies 1, 3B, 4B and 5) or race (in Studies 3A and 4A). Data for Studies 1ΓÇô5 as well as analysis code for all studies can be found on OSF: https://osf.io/zxyw2/.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_session.log:329:[codex] Participants. As pre-registered (https://osf.io/vazsm/), we recruited 1,000 participants through Prolific to complete a 3-minute survey for $0.75 (55.4% women; 43.7% men; 0.9% non-binary; Mage = 43.80; 72.3% White, 13.2% Black, 6.5% Hispanic, 7.2% Asian).
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_session.log:349:[codex] Participants. This study was pre-registered on AsPredicted (https://aspredicted.org/WYY_3PL). We recruited 302 participants to complete a 1-minute survey in exchange for a candy bar (52.52% men; 44.96% women; Mage = 25.11, 41.37% White, 10.79% Black, 4.68% Hispanic, 42.81% Asian) in a high-traffic pedestrian area at a midsize university in the Northeastern United States between March 27 and May 15, 2024. The IRB approved a waiver of informed consent, so participants were not told that they were participating in a research study.
