C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_session.log:381:[codex] On average, 17.5% of participantsΓÇÖ initially selected films featured female protagonists, with balance across conditions (p = 0.813; see Appendix Table/Section X). As shown in Figure S2B and in our primary, pre-registered OLS regression (Model 1 of Table S5), participants were significantly more likely to choose a biopic featuring a woman protagonist as their seventh and final film in the gender feedback condition (40.64% chose a biopic with a woman protagonist) than in the no gender feedback condition (20.08% chose a biopic with a woman protagonist; B = 0.206, 95% CI = [0.150, 0.261], t(998) = 7.24, p < .001, see Table S5 Model 1). These results were robust to several alternative specifications, including controlling for participant gender, race, and age, and analyzing our data with logistic regression (see Appendix Table S6 for robustness checks). In addition, as shown in Figure S2B and Table S5 (Models 5-8), and as predicted, the effect of assignment to the gender feedback condition on the likelihood of selecting a 7th film with a woman protagonist was larger than the effect of assignment to receive descriptive feedback about the percentage of initial films selected with a (1) budget above $40M (F(1, 1992) = 65.06, p < .001), (2) political leader protagonist (F(1, 1992) = 57.74, p < .001), or (3) release year after 2010 (F(1, 1992) = 12.44, p < .001) on subsequent selections of a 7th and final biopic with, respectively, a (1) budget above $40M, (2) political leader protagonist, or (3) release year after 2010 (in fact, all other types of feedback had insignificant effects on subsequent film selections).
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_session.log:393:[codex] Participants. As pre-registered (https://aspredicted.org/XGG_21R), we recruited 1,000 participants on AmazonΓÇÖs Cloudresearch to complete a 3-minute survey for $0.75 (47.6% men, 51.5% women; Mage = 42.53; 75.75% White, 9.21% Black, 4.75% Hispanic, 8.83% Asian). 
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_session.log:397:[codex] Internal motivation to respond without prejudice. To assess internal motives (e.g., image concerns) in the final author selection, we adapted four items from Plant and DevineΓÇÖs (1998) internal motivation to respond without prejudice scale (e.g., ΓÇ£Given my personal values and beliefs, an important factor in my selection of the seventh author to add to my list was my desire to promote the success of racial minorities.ΓÇ¥; CronbachΓÇÖs ╬▒ = 0.93). Items used a  1 (Strongly disagree) to 7 (Strongly agree) scale and, as pre-registered, were separately z-scored and then averaged.
