C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_v3_pass.session.log:1233:[codex] Notes: Each row reports the percentage-point increase in the likelihood that a participant's final selection had a given attribute, induced by random assignment to receive descriptive feedback about that attribute in the participant's set of initial selections, estimated via ordinary-least-squares regression with HC3 robust standard errors. Identity-target feedback estimates correspond to Model 1 of the per-study regression tables in the manuscript and Appendix (Tables 3, S3, S5, S7, and S9); comparison-attribute feedback estimates correspond to the analogous single-equation specification with the comparison attribute as both the outcome and the feedback target. The right-most column reports the p-value of the Wald F-test of equality between the identity-target and comparison-attribute feedback effects, estimated from a Zellner (1962) seemingly-unrelated regression system pairing the identity equation with each comparison equation; rejection indicates that the identity-target feedback effect is significantly larger in magnitude than the corresponding comparison-attribute feedback effect. For Study 2, the Zellner system was not pre-registered (because of the smaller sample), and the reported Wald p-values are estimated post-hoc using the same SUR specification applied to Studies 3AΓÇô4B. Comparison attributes were chosen to be domain-relevant for each selection task; in Study 4B, the comparison attributes were additionally pre-tested for importance and confirmed to be rated at least as important as the identity-target attribute. Study 1 is excluded because participants did not generate their own initial selections (the initial portfolio was stimulus-sampled), and Study 5 is excluded because its design varies the initial candidate pool's composition rather than holding it constant. + p < .10; * p < .05; ** p < .01; *** p < .001.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_v3_pass.session.log:1265:[codex]    4: Many organizations provide employees feedback on the demographics of whom theyΓÇÖve chosen to spotlight, hire, and promote, hoping to spur more diverse selections. However, it is an open question whether providing purely descriptive feedback can improve diversity. We theorized and showed that descriptive feedback highlighting low past selection rates of women or racial minorities (e.g., 5% of previous experts you interviewed were women) triggers a motivation to respond without prejudice, increasing the subsequent selection of members of underrepresented groups. Conversely, providing descriptive feedback about low selection rates of other attributes (e.g., areas of expertise, recent release dates) that doesnΓÇÖt evoke image or reputational concerns has less influence on future decisions. We demonstrated these patterns across seven pre-registered experiments (total N=6,502), including one framed field experiment (Study 2). In Study 4, we identified motivation to respond without prejudice as a mediator of the effect of descriptive feedback about past choices on future selections of women and racial minorities. Moreover, in Study 5 we showed that when women are overrepresented, the effect of descriptive feedback reverses in direction, increasing the subsequent selection of men (due to concerns about fairness), but this effect is significantly smaller in magnitude than the standard effect produced when women are underrepresented. Practically, the effects of descriptive feedback were 45-80% as large as imposing a strict quota requiring that at least one woman or racial minority be selected for a given opportunity, highlighting that descriptive feedback is a light-touch but potentially powerful intervention for shifting inclusive behaviors. 
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_v3_pass.session.log:1275:[codex]   14: We theorize that diversity-related descriptive feedback about selection decisions (e.g., the racial or gender composition of those selected for past opportunities) can be effective at promoting diversification in subsequent selection decisions even in the absence of an explicit goal or norm when it suggests past choices have lacked diversity. We further posit that such feedback can be more effective at influencing future choices than descriptive feedback about other features of selection decisions. Why? Because diversity-related feedback can draw attention to the potential reputational and self-image ramifications of choices even in the absence of an explicit goal. Specifically, we propose that when such feedback highlights the underrepresentation of women or racial minorities in past selections, it will raise concerns that past behavior could be seen as discriminatory and therefore risk rebuke. This is a reaction referred to as ΓÇ£motivation to respond without prejudiceΓÇ¥ (Plant & Devine, 1998), and it is driven by peopleΓÇÖs desire to (1) avoid negative repercussions from others (i.e., to protect their reputation; Leary & Kowalski, 1990; Lerner & Tetlock, 1999) and (2) maintain a positive self-view or self-image (Plant & Devine, 1998, 2009; Crandall & Eshleman, 2003; Apfelbaum et al., 2008). 
