C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_v3_pass.session.log:2001:[codex]  383: Notes: Each row reports the percentage-point increase in the likelihood that a participant's final selection had a given attribute, induced by random assignment to receive descriptive feedback about that attribute in the participant's set of initial selections, estimated via ordinary-least-squares regression with HC3 robust standard errors. Identity-target feedback estimates correspond to Model 1 of the per-study regression tables in the manuscript and Appendix (Tables 3, S3, S5, S7, and S9); comparison-attribute feedback estimates correspond to the analogous single-equation specification with the comparison attribute as both the outcome and the feedback target. The right-most column reports the p-value of the Wald F-test of equality between the identity-target and comparison-attribute feedback effects, estimated from a Zellner (1962) seemingly-unrelated regression system pairing the identity equation with each comparison equation; rejection indicates that the identity-target feedback effect is significantly larger in magnitude than the corresponding comparison-attribute feedback effect. For Study 2, the Zellner system was not pre-registered (because of the smaller sample), and the reported Wald p-values are estimated post-hoc using the same SUR specification applied to Studies 3AΓÇô4B. Comparison attributes were chosen to be domain-relevant for each selection task; in Study 4B, the comparison attributes were additionally pre-tested for importance and confirmed to be rated at least as important as the identity-target attribute. Study 1 is excluded because participants did not generate their own initial selections (the initial portfolio was stimulus-sampled), and Study 5 is excluded because its design varies the initial candidate pool's composition rather than holding it constant. + p < .10; * p < .05; ** p < .01; *** p < .001.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_v3_pass.session.log:2090:[codex]  149: > Our work makes two primary theoretical contributions. First, we offer new insights about how and when descriptive feedback motivates behavior change. According to Feedback Intervention Theory, feedback is most effective when paired with explicit goals, standards, or explicit injunctive norms that signal a clear gap between current performance and a desired state (Kluger & DeNisi, 1996; Schultz et al., 2007). Purely descriptive feedback is often viewed as insufficient to drive change because it lacks a directive. We show that descriptive feedback can consistently motivate behavior change in the absence of explicit prescriptions. When such feedback targets DEI-relevant attributes of past selections and suggests women or minorities have been overlooked, the feedback itself elicits reputational or self-image concerns ΓÇô specifically, internal and external motivation to respond without prejudice. In the context of diversity, an explicit goal, target, social norm or injunctive norm does not need to be coupled with feedback to induce a response because an implicit injunctive norm to avoid prejudice has already been internalized by the decision-maker. This suggests that the utility of providing descriptive feedback absent an explicit goal, target or norm lies in its ability to focus attention on past behavior in arenas where individuals already harbor self-image or reputational concerns.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_v3_pass.session.log:2095:[codex]  154: > Our work makes two primary theoretical contributions. First, we offer new insights about how and when descriptive feedback motivates behavior change. According to Feedback Intervention Theory, feedback is most effective when paired with explicit goals, standards, or explicit injunctive norms that signal a clear gap between current performance and a desired state (Kluger & DeNisi, 1996[; Locke & Latham, 2019]; Schultz et al., 2007[; Schultz et al., 2018]). Purely descriptive feedback is often viewed as insufficient to drive change because it lacks a directive. We show that descriptive feedback can consistently motivate behavior change in the absence of explicit prescriptions. When such feedback targets DEI-relevant attributes of past selections and suggests women or minorities have been overlooked, the feedback itself elicits reputational or self-image concerns ΓÇô specifically, internal and external motivation to respond without prejudice. [These two pathways operate through distinct channels. External motivation to control prejudice should be strongest when selection decisions are observable to colleagues, candidates, supervisors, customers, employees, or stakeholders, and when evaluators face legal accountability or reputational consequences for choices that appear exclusionary; in this view, firms' public DEI rhetoric is one downstream signal of these broader legal, employee, customer, and reputational pressures rather than the source of the implicit injunctive norm itself (Levi & Fried, 2024). Internal motivation to control prejudice, by contrast, reflects selectors' personally held egalitarian beliefs and their desire to view themselves as non-prejudiced decision makers, and it is the pathway most directly supported by Study 4's private-feedback design. Study 4B's null moderation by political ideology is consistent with this account, suggesting that both pathways can operate across the partisan spectrum.] In the context of diversity, an explicit goal, target, social norm or injunctive norm does not need to be coupled with feedback to induce a response because an implicit injunctive norm to avoid prejudice has already been internalized by the decision-maker. This suggests that the utility of providing descriptive feedback absent an explicit goal, target or norm lies in its ability to focus attention on past behavior in arenas where individuals already harbor self-image or reputational concerns.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_v3_pass.session.log:2167:[codex]  226: > We theorize that diversity-related descriptive feedback about selection decisions (e.g., the racial or gender composition of those selected for past opportunities) can be effective at promoting diversification in subsequent selection decisions even in the absence of an explicit goal or norm when it suggests past choices have lacked diversity. We further posit that such feedback can be more effective at influencing future choices than descriptive feedback about other features of selection decisions. Why? Because diversity-related feedback can draw attention to the potential reputational and self-image ramifications of choices even in the absence of an explicit goal. Specifically, we propose that when such feedback highlights the underrepresentation of women or racial minorities in past selections, it will raise concerns that past behavior could be seen as discriminatory and therefore risk rebuke. This is a reaction referred to as "motivation to respond without prejudice" (Plant & Devine, 1998), and it is driven by people's desire to (1) avoid negative repercussions from others (i.e., to protect their reputation; Leary & Kowalski, 1990; Lerner & Tetlock, 1999) and (2) maintain a positive self-view or self-image (Plant & Devine, 1998, 2009; Crandall & Eshleman, 2003; Apfelbaum et al., 2008).
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_v3_pass.session.log:2172:[codex]  231: > We theorize that diversity-related descriptive feedback about selection decisions (e.g., the racial or gender composition of those selected for past opportunities) can be effective at promoting diversification in subsequent selection decisions even in the absence of an explicit goal or norm when it suggests past choices have lacked diversity. We further posit that such feedback can be more effective at influencing future choices than descriptive feedback about other features of selection decisions. [Crucially, this asymmetric prediction does not rest on any assumption that participants' initial selections reflect a normatively "appropriate" or correct baseline for any attribute. Instead, we predict that descriptive feedback shifts subsequent selections only on dimensions that carry an implicit injunctive norm the feedback calls into question, and we argue this holds for race and gender but not for the comparison attributes we test.] Why? Because diversity-related feedback can draw attention to the potential reputational and self-image ramifications of choices even in the absence of an explicit goal. Specifically, we propose that when such feedback highlights the underrepresentation of women or racial minorities in past selections, it will raise concerns that past behavior could be seen as discriminatory and therefore risk rebuke. This is a reaction referred to as "motivation to respond without prejudice" (Plant & Devine, 1998), and it is driven by people's desire to (1) avoid negative repercussions from others (i.e., to protect their reputation; Leary & Kowalski, 1990; Lerner & Tetlock, 1999) and (2) maintain a positive self-view or self-image (Plant & Devine, 1998, 2009; Crandall & Eshleman, 2003; Apfelbaum et al., 2008).
