C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_v3_pass.session.log:3336:[codex] 141:> Our work makes two primary theoretical contributions. First, we offer new insights about how and when descriptive feedback motivates behavior change. According to Feedback Intervention Theory, feedback is most effective when paired with explicit goals, standards, or explicit injunctive norms that signal a clear gap between current performance and a desired state (Kluger & DeNisi, 1996; Schultz et al., 2007). Purely descriptive feedback is often viewed as insufficient to drive change because it lacks a directive. We show that descriptive feedback can consistently motivate behavior change in the absence of explicit prescriptions. When such feedback targets DEI-relevant attributes of past selections and suggests women or minorities have been overlooked, the feedback itself elicits reputational or self-image concerns ΓÇô specifically, internal and external motivation to respond without prejudice. [External motivation to respond without prejudice should be most consequential when selection decisions are observable to colleagues, candidates, supervisors, customers, employees, or stakeholders; firmsΓÇÖ public DEI rhetoric is therefore one downstream signal of these broader legal, employee, customer, and reputational pressures rather than the source of the implicit injunctive norm itself (Levi & Fried, 2024). Internal motivation to respond without prejudice, by contrast, reflects evaluatorsΓÇÖ own egalitarian commitments and desire to view themselves as non-prejudiced decision makers, and it is the pathway most directly supported by Study 4ΓÇÖs private-feedback design. This distinction also helps interpret Study 4BΓÇÖs null moderation by political ideology: feedback may move evaluators across the partisan spectrum when either external accountability or internal egalitarian self-image makes the prospect of appearing prejudiced consequential.] In the context of diversity, an explicit goal, target, social norm or injunctive norm does not need to be coupled with feedback to induce a response because an implicit injunctive norm to avoid prejudice has already been internalized by the decision-maker. This suggests that the utility of providing descriptive feedback absent an explicit goal, target or norm lies in its ability to focus attention on past behavior in arenas where individuals already harbor self-image or reputational concerns.
