C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\r2_manuscript_changes.md:150:> Our work makes two primary theoretical contributions. First, we offer new insights about how and when descriptive feedback motivates behavior change. According to Feedback Intervention Theory, feedback is most effective when paired with explicit goals, standards, or explicit injunctive norms that signal a clear gap between current performance and a desired state (Kluger & DeNisi, 1996; Schultz et al., 2007). Purely descriptive feedback is often viewed as insufficient to drive change because it lacks a directive. We show that descriptive feedback can consistently motivate behavior change in the absence of explicit prescriptions. When such feedback targets DEI-relevant attributes of past selections and suggests women or minorities have been overlooked, the feedback itself elicits reputational or self-image concerns – specifically, internal and external motivation to respond without prejudice. In the context of diversity, an explicit goal, target, social norm or injunctive norm does not need to be coupled with feedback to induce a response because an implicit injunctive norm to avoid prejudice has already been internalized by the decision-maker. This suggests that the utility of providing descriptive feedback absent an explicit goal, target or norm lies in its ability to focus attention on past behavior in arenas where individuals already harbor self-image or reputational concerns.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\r2_manuscript_changes.md:155:> Our work makes two primary theoretical contributions. First, we offer new insights about how and when descriptive feedback motivates behavior change. According to Feedback Intervention Theory, feedback is most effective when paired with explicit goals, standards, or explicit injunctive norms that signal a clear gap between current performance and a desired state (Kluger & DeNisi, 1996[; Locke & Latham, 2019]; Schultz et al., 2007[; Schultz et al., 2018]). Purely descriptive feedback is often viewed as insufficient to drive change because it lacks a directive. We show that descriptive feedback can consistently motivate behavior change in the absence of explicit prescriptions. When such feedback targets DEI-relevant attributes of past selections and suggests women or minorities have been overlooked, the feedback itself elicits reputational or self-image concerns – specifically, internal and external motivation to respond without prejudice. [External motivation to respond without prejudice operates when selection decisions are observable to colleagues, candidates, supervisors, customers, employees, or stakeholders, and is sustained primarily by anti-discrimination law and broader reputational pressures. Although many U.S. firms have recently pulled back from their public DEI rhetoric, such rhetoric is best understood as one downstream signal of these broader pressures rather than as their source (Levi & Fried, 2024), so the external pathway should remain operative even as organizational DEI commitments ebb and flow. Internal motivation to respond without prejudice, by contrast, reflects evaluators' own egalitarian commitments and desire to view themselves as non-prejudiced decision makers.] In the context of diversity, an explicit goal, target, social norm or injunctive norm does not need to be coupled with feedback to induce a response because an implicit injunctive norm to avoid prejudice has already been internalized by the decision-maker. This suggests that the utility of providing descriptive feedback absent an explicit goal, target or norm lies in its ability to focus attention on past behavior in arenas where individuals already harbor self-image or reputational concerns.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\r2_manuscript_changes.md:231:> We theorize that diversity-related descriptive feedback about selection decisions (e.g., the racial or gender composition of those selected for past opportunities) can be effective at promoting diversification in subsequent selection decisions even in the absence of an explicit goal or norm when it suggests past choices have lacked diversity. We further posit that such feedback can be more effective at influencing future choices than descriptive feedback about other features of selection decisions. Why? Because diversity-related feedback can draw attention to the potential reputational and self-image ramifications of choices even in the absence of an explicit goal. Specifically, we propose that when such feedback highlights the underrepresentation of women or racial minorities in past selections, it will raise concerns that past behavior could be seen as discriminatory and therefore risk rebuke. This is a reaction referred to as "motivation to respond without prejudice" (Plant & Devine, 1998), and it is driven by people's desire to (1) avoid negative repercussions from others (i.e., to protect their reputation; Leary & Kowalski, 1990; Lerner & Tetlock, 1999) and (2) maintain a positive self-view or self-image (Plant & Devine, 1998, 2009; Crandall & Eshleman, 2003; Apfelbaum et al., 2008).
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\r2_manuscript_changes.md:236:> We theorize that diversity-related descriptive feedback about selection decisions (e.g., the racial or gender composition of those selected for past opportunities) can be effective at promoting diversification in subsequent selection decisions even in the absence of an explicit goal or norm when it suggests past choices have lacked diversity. We further posit that such feedback can be more effective at influencing future choices than descriptive feedback about other features of selection decisions. [This prediction does not assume that participants' initial selections reflect a normatively "appropriate" or correct level for any attribute. Instead, we predict that descriptive feedback shifts subsequent selections on dimensions that carry an implicit injunctive norm the feedback calls into question, which we argue is true of race and gender but not of the comparison attributes we test.] Why? Because diversity-related feedback can draw attention to the potential reputational and self-image ramifications of choices even in the absence of an explicit goal. Specifically, we propose that when such feedback highlights the underrepresentation of women or racial minorities in past selections, it will raise concerns that past behavior could be seen as discriminatory and therefore risk rebuke. This is a reaction referred to as "motivation to respond without prejudice" (Plant & Devine, 1998), and it is driven by people's desire to (1) avoid negative repercussions from others (i.e., to protect their reputation; Leary & Kowalski, 1990; Lerner & Tetlock, 1999) and (2) maintain a positive self-view or self-image (Plant & Devine, 1998, 2009; Crandall & Eshleman, 2003; Apfelbaum et al., 2008).
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_consistency_pass.session.log:126:[codex]   15: We ran a new, pre-registered study (N = 300) to confirm that the attributes of NPR experts selected in Study 1 summarized alongside their gender were rated as just as important as gender. This new study helps address the concern that differences in the importance of feedback about prior selections could explain our effects.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_consistency_pass.session.log:152:[codex]   41: RESPONSE: Thank you for this suggestion. We ran the post-test you proposed and incorporated the result into the Methods section of Study 1 (p. X). Specifically, in new pre-registered study ([link to AsPredicted]), we recruited 300 Prolific participants to rate the importance of different attributes of experts selected to appear on NPR.  Specifically, our Study 1 offers participants feedback about the gender, age, location and employment status of a panel of 6? NPR experts who they selected for [what was the selection about again? Remind reader!].  Our new study randomly assigned each participant to rate the importance of one of these four attributes of NPR experts (specifically: how many were women, how many worked at a university, how many were under 50 years old, or how many were based on the West Coast of the United States) on a scale from 1 = XX to 7 = XX. . Two of the three non-gender attributes were rated as significantly more important than gender (ΓÇ£were womenΓÇ¥; Mean Importance = 3.64, SD = 1.76, n = 76): ΓÇ£worked at a universityΓÇ¥ (Mean Importance = 4.67, SD = 1.60; t(148.8) = ΓêÆ3.76, p < .001, d = ΓêÆ0.61) and ΓÇ£were under 50 years oldΓÇ¥ (Mean Importance = 4.44, SD = 1.73; t(149.0) = ΓêÆ2.81, p = .006, d = ΓêÆ0.46). The third, ΓÇ£based on the West Coast of the United States,ΓÇ¥ did not differ significantly from gender in importance (Mean Importance = 3.37, SD = 1.75; t(149.0) = 0.95, p = .343, d = +0.16). These results suggest that differences in the perceived importance of the type of feedback participants received about their selections in Study 1 cannot account for why only feedback about gender moved subsequent selections.
