C:\Users\jcerv\AppData\Local\Temp\manuscript_fresh.txt:103:On average, 17.5% of participants’ initially selected films featured female protagonists, with balance across conditions (p = 0.813; see Appendix Table S5). As shown in Figure S2B and in our primary, pre-registered OLS regression (Model 1 of Table S5), participants were significantly more likely to choose a biopic featuring a woman protagonist as their seventh and final film in the gender feedback condition (40.64% chose a biopic with a woman protagonist) than in the no gender feedback condition (20.08% chose a biopic with a woman protagonist; B = 0.206, 95% CI = [0.150, 0.261], t(998) = 7.24, p < .001, see Table S5 Model 1). These results were robust to several alternative specifications, including controlling for participant gender, race, and age, and analyzing our data with logistic regression (see Appendix Table S6 for robustness checks). In addition, as shown in Figure S2B and Table S5 (Models 5-8), and as predicted, the effect of assignment to the gender feedback condition on the likelihood of selecting a 7th film with a woman protagonist was larger than the effect of assignment to receive descriptive feedback about the percentage of initial films selected with a (1) budget above $40M (F(1, 1992) = 65.06, p < .001), (2) political leader protagonist (F(1, 1992) = 57.74, p < .001), or (3) release year after 2010 (F(1, 1992) = 12.44, p < .001) on subsequent selections of a 7th and final biopic with, respectively, a (1) budget above $40M, (2) political leader protagonist, or (3) release year after 2010 (in fact, all other types of feedback had insignificant effects on subsequent film selections).
C:\Users\jcerv\AppData\Local\Temp\manuscript_fresh.txt:128:In this study, we replicate our key findings from Study 4A, but this time we provide feedback about the gender (rather than race) of the initial selectees. Prior to this study, we conducted a pretest (N = 550) rating 21 candidate author attributes on importance for selecting authors (see Appendix Study S3 for full details); allowing us to select three comparison attributes that did not differ significantly from gender on rated importance.
C:\Users\jcerv\AppData\Local\Temp\manuscript_fresh.txt:184:                Across seven pre-registered experiments, including a framed field study in a real organization, we investigate the impact of providing descriptive feedback about the gender and racial diversity of past candidate selections on evaluators’ future choices. In Studies 1-5 we demonstrate that when women (or racial minorities) are underrepresented in candidate pools, giving participants feedback about the fraction of women (or racial minorities) they initially select increases the likelihood that they will subsequently choose to add a woman (or racial minority) to their portfolio. By contrast, when participants receive descriptive feedback about the fraction of selectees with other domain-relevant attributes that are DEI-irrelevant (e.g., the fraction of Technologists on a panel instead of the fraction of women on that panel), it does not have the same impact on their subsequent selections (i.e., they are less likely to subsequently select a Technologist).[17] In Studies 4A and 4B, we identify people’s motivation to respond without prejudice as a key mechanism underlying the effect of descriptive feedback on people’s subsequent DEI-related selection decisions. We find that both internal and external motivation to respond without prejudice mediates the relationship between receiving descriptive feedback about past selectees and making more gender-or-racially-diverse future candidate selections. 
