52:We expect that a reputational or image concern is activated only after participants receive descriptive feedback suggesting that women and minorities have been vastly underrepresented in their past selections compared to the U.S. population. If underrepresentation of any group is responsible for our effects, then if the descriptive feedback we provided on some other selection attribute (say, the age of prior selectees) suggested a massive underrepresentation (say, of people over 50), this might drive a similar reaction. We conducted an additional analysis to try to address this possibility. Assuming that selecting zero options with a given attribute would always signal underrepresentation, we test the hypothesis that feedback shifts in who is subsequently selected to make up for underrepresentation not just when it comes to race and gender but on any dimension. To examine this hypothesis, we pooled data from Studies 2, 3A, 3B, and 4B (clustering standard errors by participant). We cluster standard errors by participant because each respondent contributes multiple rows to this pooled dataset: one row tracking the race or gender-feedback effect they were assigned to, plus one row for each comparison attribute featured in their study. We only retain observations involving participants who made an initial set of selections that included zero books or movies with a given attribute (e.g., a set of films in Study 3A that included zero films released after 2010, or a set of books in Study 4B that included zero books with women authors).[1] We find that among participants who selected zero women or racial minorities initially, across these studies, receiving this feedback (that they had selected no women or racial minorities) significantly increases the likelihood of selecting a woman or racial minority as their final selection, respectively, by 22.50 percentage points (Woman: +27.59 pp; Racial Minority: +9.77; p < .001, N = 864). Among participants who initially selected zero movies, books, or authors with any of the other attributes under study (e.g., budget, year of release, or protagonist’s profession), feedback informing them that none of their selectees had those other attributes did not significantly alter their probability of subsequently selecting an additional movie, book, or author with the relevant attribute (b = 7.25 percentage points; p = .19, N = 414). A Wald test of the difference between the two pooled coefficients confirms that the pooled effect of feedback on subsequent choices is significantly larger when feedback is about the race or gender of initial selections than when it is about other features of initial selections (p = .016, 95% CI [+2.87, +27.63]). We have added a footnote to the General Discussion (p. X), anchored on the sentence where we first state the differential effect of race or gender feedback versus comparison-attribute feedback. The footnote summarizes the cross-study rule-out and points readers to Appendix Section S[X] for the full per-cell analysis. We hope these additional analyses sufficiently address your comment.
125:[1] We exclude Study 4A from this analysis because no participants in that study made initial selections containing zero of any of the comparison attributes, meaning there is no comparable “zero-baseline” cell to contrast against the race/gender feedback effect.

