C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_placement.md:3:**A. Keep at the end of the Study 4 Discussion, split into its own paragraph.** Pros: This would keep the analysis close to Study 4B, which is the study the DE singled out as especially persuasive, and it would make the Study 4B importance-pretest callback easy to see. It would also allow a direct response-letter pointer to the Study 4B Discussion. Cons: The logical flow is weak because the preceding sentence is about political moderation and partisan generality, whereas the zero-baseline analysis is about whether participants respond to any highlighted absence or specifically to feedback that activates an implicit injunctive norm. Reviewer expectation-setting also suffers because a pooled analysis across Studies 2, 3A, 3B, and 4B feels like a convenience add-on inside a Study 4-specific wrap-up. Verdict: Defensible only as a minimal repair; it cleans the broken prose but does not solve JC’s core concern about theoretical motivation.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_placement.md:5:**B. Move to the Study 5 preamble as a follow-up analysis to the mini meta-analysis.** Pros: This has the best logical flow. The Study 5 preamble already asks whether feedback effects depend on initial representation, and the mini meta-analysis tests that question continuously; the zero-baseline analysis then tests the clearest discrete case and adds the comparison-attribute control. Reviewer expectation-setting improves because the DE’s alternative explanation is addressed where the manuscript is already motivating Study 5’s manipulation of baseline representation. The Study 4B callback remains available because Study 4B is one of the pooled studies and its importance-pretested comparison attributes help support the interpretation. The response letter also becomes coherent: it can say the manuscript now reports the analysis in the Study 5 preamble, where the surrounding prose already frames why baseline representation matters. Cons: The answer is no longer adjacent to the Study 4B Discussion, so the response letter must explicitly name the new location. Verdict: Best option because it makes the analysis theoretically earned rather than appended.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_placement.md:9:**D. Move the analysis into the Appendix only, with one manuscript sentence pointing to it.** Pros: This is the cleanest way to preserve the main-text flow and avoid making a lower-powered subset analysis carry too much argumentative weight. It also reduces page pressure and keeps the technical details with Table R1-style reporting. Cons: It under-serves the DE’s request because the core alternative explanation would be mostly offstage, and the response letter would sound stronger than the manuscript if the main text only gestures to the analysis. It also wastes the natural Study 5 bridge, where the zero-baseline result can clarify why Study 5 manipulates initial representation experimentally. The Study 4B callback opportunity would be thin because the main text would not visibly connect the zero-baseline check to the importance-pretested comparison attributes. Verdict: Useful if space is the overriding constraint, but too quiet for a reviewer concern that should be visibly addressed.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_placement.md:15:Recommend Option B: move the zero-baseline pooled analysis to the Study 5 preamble, immediately after the mini meta-analysis paragraph and before the Study 5 experimental design paragraph. This location makes the analysis a complementary test of the same baseline-representation logic already motivating Study 5, while also answering the DE’s alternative explanation with a direct comparison between race and gender feedback and comparison-attribute feedback.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_placement.md:23:### Subsection 2: The new zero-baseline insertion at the recommended location
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_placement.md:25:The continuous interaction analysis above captures whether feedback effects decline as the initial share of women or racial minorities rises. We also conducted a complementary analysis focused on the clearest underrepresentation case, participants whose initial selections contained zero candidates with a given attribute. This zero-baseline test also lets us address whether participants simply responded to any highlighted absence, rather than responding specifically to feedback that made an implicit injunctive norm salient. Pooling Studies 2, 3A, 3B, and 4B, excluding Study 4A because no participant began with zero of any comparison attribute, race and gender feedback raised the probability of selecting a racial minority or woman, respectively, by 22.50 percentage points (*p* < .001, *N* = 864). By contrast, feedback about other attributes did not significantly shift subsequent selections among participants whose initial portfolios contained zero of that attribute (effect = +7.25 percentage points, *p* = .19, *N* = 414). A Wald test confirmed that the difference between these pooled coefficients was significant (*p* = .016), with full results reported in Appendix Section S[X]. Thus, even when the initial portfolio contains the same stark absence of the feedback target, participants respond more strongly to race and gender feedback than to comparison-attribute feedback, consistent with our account that descriptive feedback is most powerful when it signals a possible violation of an implicit injunctive norm.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_placement.md:29:RESPONSE: Thank you for raising this alternative. We agree it is worth testing directly, and we report a follow-up analysis below in Table R1. We have added a short cross-study analysis to the Study 5 preamble (p. X), where the manuscript already reanalyzes Studies 2, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B to test whether feedback effects are larger when initial selections include fewer women or racial minorities. The new paragraph reports the zero-baseline version of that test, restricted to participants whose initial selections contained zero candidates with a given attribute, and shows that race and gender feedback produced a larger shift than comparison-attribute feedback under the same zero-baseline condition. We believe this placement makes the alternative explanation and the theoretical claim more explicit at the point where the manuscript motivates Study 5’s experimental manipulation of initial representation.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_placement.md:33:Stem: After reviewing the zero-baseline figure, how important was this figure in shaping your impression of whether the results support the authors’ interpretation that race and gender feedback operate differently from comparison-attribute feedback?
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_relocation.md:1:# Codex Recommendation: Zero-Baseline Relocation (round 2)
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_relocation.md:11:A. Extend the Study 4 preamble. Strengths: this is the best conceptual fit because line 99 already tells readers that Study 4 addresses whether comparison attributes might be less important than race or gender, and the zero-baseline analysis addresses the sibling concern that comparison attributes might already have been used appropriately in participants’ initial selections. It lets the manuscript answer both prongs of the DE’s critique in one place, before Study 4A and Study 4B show mechanism evidence. Weakness: it previews a pooled analysis that includes Study 4B before readers have seen Study 4B, but line 99 already previews Study 4B’s importance pretest, so this is consistent with the current structure.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_relocation.md:15:C. General Discussion theoretical-contributions paragraph. Strengths: lines 171-172 already make the theoretical claim that descriptive feedback activates implicit injunctive norms for race and gender, so the zero-baseline analysis could support that claim. Weakness: this is too late for a first-time reader because the empirical comparison between race/gender feedback and comparison-attribute feedback has already done its work by then.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_relocation.md:19:E. Keep the current Study 5 preamble placement. Strengths: the nearby Study 5 setup discusses how feedback effects vary with the initial proportion of women or racial minorities, which gives the zero-baseline analysis a superficial baseline connection. Weakness: lines 135-141 are about whether the race/gender feedback effect depends on the initial proportion selected and therefore motivates Study 5’s experimental manipulation; the zero-baseline analysis asks whether the race/gender versus comparison-attribute differential is real or an artifact of appropriate initial use. That is a different question, so the current placement blurs the logic.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_relocation.md:21:F. Footnote at the Study 4B Results F-test paragraph. Strengths: line 127 is the closest local place where the manuscript formally tests the gender-feedback versus comparison-attribute differential for the importance-matched Study 4B attributes. Weakness: the zero-baseline analysis pools Studies 2, 3A, 3B, and 4B, so placing it in a Study 4B footnote makes it look like a local Study 4B robustness check rather than a cross-study response to the DE’s broader concern.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_relocation.md:25:The recommended placement addresses both prongs of the DE’s critique better than the Study 5 preamble because line 99 already raises the comparison-attribute robustness problem and answers the importance prong. Adding the zero-baseline analysis there lets readers see the second prong immediately: even among participants whose initial selections contained zero of an attribute, comparison-attribute feedback did not move later selections the way race and gender feedback did. By contrast, the Study 5 preamble is organized around a different empirical bridge, moving from the continuous baseline by feedback interaction in Table 4 to a randomized manipulation of women’s underrepresentation versus overrepresentation in Study 5.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_relocation.md:27:The current text dump does not show a clean standalone paragraph at the current site. The zero-baseline material is appended to the Study 4 Discussion at line 133, immediately before Study 5, and is followed by a corrupted duplicate fragment. That is another reason to move the material out of the Study 4 to Study 5 transition and restore the transition to its Study 5 logic.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_relocation.md:31:Delete the following zero-baseline material from the paragraph at line 133, beginning after the sentence ending with “Kirgios et al., 2022).” and before “Study 5”:
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_relocation.md:33:> Building on this, we conducted a pooled analysis across Studies 2, 3A, 3B, and 4B (excluding Study 4A, where no participant began with zero of any comparison attribute), restricting our sample to participants whose initial selections contained zero candidates with a given attribute. Selecting zero of an attribute is a clear signal of underrepresentation that should provoke a response to feedback regardless of which attribute is summarized. Race and gender feedback raised the probability of selecting a racial minority or woman, respectively, by 22.50 percentage points (*p* < .001, *N* = 864), whereas feedback about other attributes did not significantly shift subsequent selections among participants whose initial portfolios contained zero of that attribute (effect = +7.25 percentage points, *p* = .19, *N* = 414). A Wald test confirms the difference between the two pooled coefficients is significant (*p* = .016). Full results appear in Appendix Section S[X].
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_relocation.md:43:> Relatedly, we tested whether the smaller effects of comparison-attribute feedback could be explained by participants already using those attributes appropriately in their initial selections. We pooled data from Studies 2, 3A, 3B, and 4B, excluding Study 4A because no participant began with zero of any comparison attribute, and restricted the analysis to participants whose initial selections contained zero of a given attribute. If the race and gender effects simply reflected participants reacting to the absence of an attribute from their initial portfolios, comparison-attribute feedback should also shift later selections in this subsample. It did not. Race and gender feedback increased the probability of selecting a racial minority or woman by 22.50 percentage points (*p* < .001, *N* = 864), whereas feedback about comparison attributes increased the probability of selecting an option with the focal attribute by 7.25 percentage points, an effect that was not statistically significant (*p* = .19, *N* = 414). A Wald test confirmed that the pooled race and gender feedback effect was significantly larger than the pooled comparison-attribute feedback effect (*p* = .016; see Appendix Section S[X]).
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_relocation.md:47:Thank you for raising the possibility that comparison attributes may have been used “appropriately” in participants’ initial selections. We now address this concern in the Study 4 preamble, alongside the importance-pretest evidence, and report a pooled zero-baseline analysis showing that feedback continues to have a larger effect for race and gender than for comparison attributes among participants whose initial portfolios contained none of the focal attribute. Full model details appear in Appendix Section S[X].
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_round3.md:1:# Codex Recommendation (Round 3): Zero-Baseline Placement
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_round3.md:5:Recommend Option B: extend the Study 4 preamble with framing only and move all zero-baseline statistics to the Appendix, because line 99 is already where the comparison-attribute rule-out logic lives and this placement introduces no Study 4B experimental statistics before Study 4B Results.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_round3.md:15:D. Study 5 preamble after the mini-meta: Reject. Study 5’s preamble is about whether the race and gender feedback effect depends on baseline representation, whereas the zero-baseline test addresses whether comparison-attribute feedback was weaker because participants had already used those attributes appropriately.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_round3.md:37:We further considered the possibility that participants may have already used the comparison attributes appropriately in their initial selections, leaving less room for descriptive feedback about those attributes to change subsequent choices. We report a pooled zero-baseline analysis in Appendix Section S[X] that restricts attention to cases in which participants initially selected zero options with a given attribute. This provides a conservative test of whether feedback about an attribute’s complete absence produces the same pattern for race and gender as for the other attributes summarized in our studies.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_round3.md:39:Study 5 cleanup: delete the current zero-baseline paragraph from the Study 5 preamble. This is the paragraph beginning “Building on this, we conducted a pooled analysis across Studies 2, 3A, 3B, and 4B” and ending with “Finally, it ruled out the possibility that our effects were driven by perceptions of which attributes were considered most important.” Do not replace it in Study 5. Let the mini-meta paragraph continue directly into the Study 5 experimental motivation.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_round3.md:43:Exact insertion point: create a new Appendix section, preferably after the existing Study 4 comparison-attribute material or after the appendix table that reports the race and gender versus comparison-attribute regressions. Suggested title: “Appendix Section S[X]: Zero-Baseline Analysis of Initial Nonselection.”
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_round3.md:47:To address the possibility that descriptive feedback about comparison attributes had weaker effects because participants had already represented those attributes appropriately in their initial selections, we conducted a pooled zero-baseline analysis across Studies 2, 3A, 3B, and 4B. We excluded Study 4A because no participant began with zero of any comparison attribute. The analysis restricted the sample to participant-attribute observations in which a participant’s initial selections contained zero options with the focal attribute, and clustered standard errors by participant. Selecting zero options with an attribute provides a conservative signal of underrepresentation that should leave room for descriptive feedback to affect a later selection regardless of which attribute is summarized.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_round3.md:49:Among participants who initially selected zero women or racial minorities, race or gender feedback increased the probability of subsequently selecting a woman or racial minority by 22.50 percentage points (*p* < .001, *N* = 864). By contrast, among participants who initially selected zero options with one of the comparison attributes, feedback about that attribute did not significantly increase the probability of subsequently selecting an option with that attribute (effect = +7.25 percentage points, *p* = .19, *N* = 414). A Wald test confirmed that the pooled race and gender coefficient was significantly larger than the pooled comparison-attribute coefficient (*p* = .016, 95% CI [+2.87, +27.63]). The accompanying table should report the coefficient, standard error, confidence interval, *p* value, and *N* for the race and gender zero-baseline estimate, the comparison-attribute zero-baseline estimate, and the Wald difference test.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_round3.md:53:Replace the current response to the DE’s zero-baseline question with:
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_round3.md:55:Thank you for raising this possibility. We now address it in two places. First, in the Study 4 preamble, where the manuscript already discusses whether comparison attributes can rule out alternative explanations for our findings, we added text explicitly considering the possibility that participants may have already used those attributes appropriately in their initial selections. Second, we report a new pooled zero-baseline analysis in Appendix Section S[X]. Because this analysis pools across Study 4B, we refer readers to the Appendix from the Study 4 preamble rather than reporting those coefficients before Study 4B Results.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_round3.md:57:Our logic was that selecting zero options with a given attribute provides a conservative signal of underrepresentation. If feedback simply corrects any initially inappropriate level of representation, then feedback about the complete absence of a comparison attribute should also shift subsequent selections. To examine this possibility, we pooled data from Studies 2, 3A, 3B, and 4B, excluding Study 4A because no participant in that study began with zero of any comparison attribute. Among participants who selected zero women or racial minorities initially, race or gender feedback significantly increased the probability of selecting a woman or racial minority as the final selection by 22.50 percentage points (*p* < .001, *N* = 864). By contrast, among participants who initially selected zero options with a comparison attribute, feedback about that attribute did not significantly increase the probability of selecting an option with the relevant attribute (effect = +7.25 percentage points, *p* = .19, *N* = 414). A Wald test confirmed that the pooled effect of feedback was significantly larger for race and gender than for comparison attributes (*p* = .016, 95% CI [+2.87, +27.63]).
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_round3.md:59:These analyses cannot prove that participants never considered comparison attributes appropriately at the initial selection stage. However, they help rule out the stronger version of the alternative explanation. Even in cases where participants initially selected zero options with a comparison attribute, feedback about that absence did not produce the same pattern as feedback about the absence of women or racial minorities. Thus, the differential held even under a conservative zero-baseline test.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_zero_baseline_round3.md:77:Round 1 failed because the Study 5 preamble is organized around a different question: whether the effect depends on baseline representation. This recommendation removes the zero-baseline paragraph from Study 5.
