C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\katy_2026-05-09\audit_diff.txt:21:-As shown in Figure 3A and Model 1 of Table 2, participants selected a significantly higher proportion of women experts in the gender feedback condition (46.2% women experts selected) than in the no gender feedback condition (33.7% women experts selected; B = 0.125, 95% CI = [0.093, 0.157], t(997) = 7.58, p < .001). The effect was robust to controlling for participant demographics (Appendix Table S1) and was significantly larger than the effect of offering feedback on each of the three other attributes featured in this study — age (over 50), geography (located on the West Coast) and professional affiliation (university based) — on increasing selections of experts selected with the described attribute (see Appendix for a complete discussion of the systems of simultaneous equations and Wald tests employed, all ps ≤ .010; see Table 2). [FOOTNOTE: See Appendix Section XX for a detailed description on the formal test of determining whether the effect of gender and race feedback is significantly larger than all other comparison attributes (Zellner, 1962).]
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\katy_2026-05-09\audit_diff.txt:23:+As shown in Figure 3A and Model 1 of Table 2, participants selected a significantly higher proportion of women experts in the gender feedback condition (46.2% women experts selected) than in the no gender feedback condition (33.7% women experts selected; B = 0.125, 95% CI = [0.093, 0.157], t(997) = 7.58, p < .001). The effect was robust to controlling for participant demographics (Appendix Table S1).	To formally test whether offering feedback about the percentage of past experts who were women had a larger effect on the subsequent selection of women experts than offering feedback about other attributes had on the subsequent selection of experts with those attributes, we constructed three systems of simultaneous equations (Zellner, 1962). For each system, we included a pair of equations: one modeling the effect of random assignment to receive gender feedback and one modeling the effect of random assignment to receive feedback on another expert attribute (i.e., past selectees who were under 50 years old, based on the West Coast, or worked at a university, see Table 2, Models 5-8). We then used Wald tests to compare the treatment effects estimated in the paired equations, which confirmed that the effect of assignment to the gender feedback condition on the proportion of women experts selected was significantly larger than the effects of assignment to receive descriptive feedback about the percentage of past experts who were (1) under 50 years old (F(1, 3988) = 6.63, p = .010), (2) based on the West Coast (F(1, 3988) = 8.35, p = .004), or (3) worked at a university (F(1, 3988) = 12.84, p < .001) on subsequent selections of experts with those respective attributes. This pattern of findings held across stimuli sets (see footnote 2). 
