C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\katy_2026-05-09\paragraph_diff.txt:22:BEFORE: 	The effect was robust to demographic controls (Appendix Table S1) and was significantly larger than the effect of feedback about each of the three comparison attributes (Wald tests, all ps ≤ .010; see Table 2).To formally test whether offering feedback about the percentage of past experts who were women had a larger effect on the subsequent selection of women experts than offering feedback about other attributes had on the subsequent selection of experts with those attributes, we constructed three systems of simultaneous equations (Zellner, 1962). For each system, we included a pair of equations: one modeling the effect of random assignment to receive gender feedback and one modeling the effect of random assignment to receive feedback on another expert attribute (i.e., past selectees who were under 50 years old, based on the West Coast, or worked at a university, see Table 2, Models 5-8). We then used Wald tests to compare the treatment effects estimated in the paired equations, which confirmed that the effect of assignment to the gender feedback condition on the proportion of women experts selected was significantly larger than the effects of assignment to receive descriptive feedback about the percentage of past experts who were (1) under 50 years old (F(1, 3988) = 6.63, p = .010), (2) based on the West Coast (F(1, 3988) = 8.35, p = .004), or (3) worked at a university (F(1, 3988) = 12.84, p < .001) on subsequent selections of experts with those respective attributes. This pattern of findings held across stimuli sets.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\katy_2026-05-09\paragraph_diff.txt:24:AFTER:  As shown in Figure 3A and Model 1 of Table 2, participants selected a significantly higher proportion of women experts in the gender feedback condition (46.2% women experts selected) than in the no gender feedback condition (33.7% women experts selected; B = 0.125, 95% CI = [0.093, 0.157], t(997) = 7.58, p < .001). The effect was robust to controlling for participant demographics (Appendix Table S1) and was significantly larger than the effect of offering feedback on each of the three other attributes featured in this study — age (over 50), geography (located on the West Coast) and professional affiliation (university based) — on increasing selections of experts selected with the described attribute (see Appendix for a complete discussion of the systems of simultaneous equations and Wald tests employed, all ps ≤ .010; see Table 2). [FOOTNOTE: See Appendix Section XX for a detailed description on the formal test of determining whether the effect of gender and race feedback is significantly larger than all other comparison attributes (Zellner, 1962).]
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\katy_2026-05-09\paragraph_diff.txt:32:BEFORE: 	In Study 2, we conducted a framed field experiment (Harrison & List, 2004) to extend our key findings in an in-person, real choice environment in which participants were not aware they were under study. According to Harrison & List (2004, p. 1014), a framed field experiment is “one that uses participants from the specific population of interest (a nonstandard subject pool) and incorporates field context into the commodity, task, or information participants use, making the setting more realistic than a conventional lab experiment.” Our framed field experiment extends our prior findings by examining whether they apply in a setting where people were making real decisions with real impact on their community and were unaware that they were in a research study. Specifically, hHere we tested whether our key effect of descriptive feedback on selection decisions held when evaluators were making incentive-compatible choices about which prominent figures they would like to feature in a public display in their organization. 
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\katy_2026-05-09\paragraph_diff.txt:59:BEFORE: Procedure. The procedure in this study was nearly identical to the procedure described in Study 3A, but we changed  with a few small differences. First, the set of 25 biopics participants could choose to feature in a Facebook advertisement differed — the selection set of biopics to includein this study included 19 films featuring male protagonists and 6 featuring female protagonists (24% of the protagonist pool were women). ParticipantsP Second, participants also began by selecting an initial portfolio of six films for inclusion in the Facebook advertising campaign instead of seven (to establish our results generalize across selection set size). TheFinally, the brief description provided of each film did not state the length of the film; instead, it presented information about the film protagonist’s profession (e.g., “A film about George W. Bush. Who was he? 43rd U.S. President.”). 
