C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\claude_zero_baseline_relocation.md:72:> We further considered the possibility, raised by reviewers, that participants may have already been using the comparison attributes appropriately in their initial selections, leaving little room for feedback about those attributes to shift behavior. To address this, we examined the subset of participants whose initial selections contained zero candidates with the focal attribute, where appropriate prior use cannot account for non-response to feedback. Pooling participants across Studies 2, 3A, 3B, and 4B (Study 4A is excluded because no participant began with zero of any comparison attribute), the differential effect held: race or gender feedback raised the probability of selecting a racial minority or woman by 22.50 percentage points (*p* < .001, *N* = 864), whereas comparison-attribute feedback shifted subsequent selections by only +7.25 percentage points (*p* = .19, *N* = 414), a difference confirmed by a Wald test (*p* = .016). Full results are reported in Appendix Section S[X].
