C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\claude_zero_baseline_placement.md:7:**Against:** The analysis pools Studies 2, 3A, 3B, 4B (not Study 4A). Putting a cross-study re-analysis inside an individual study's Discussion misleads the reader about scope. Even with a paragraph break, this would be the only cross-study re-analysis tucked inside any single-study discussion in the paper, breaking the manuscript's structural pattern. Does not motivate Study 5 (which already motivates itself with the mini-meta). Leaves the analysis feeling like a tack-on, exactly the problem JC flagged.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\claude_zero_baseline_placement.md:11:**For:** The Study 5 preamble already contains a sister analysis (the mini-meta) testing the same theoretical claim — that descriptive feedback operates through perceived underrepresentation — using nearly the same studies. The mini-meta tests the continuous form (proportion × feedback) and pools across 2, 3A, 3B, 4A, 4B. The zero-baseline analysis tests the discrete extreme (initial = 0) and adds the comparison-attribute contrast, pooling across 2, 3A, 3B, 4B. They are conceptually complementary, not redundant. Co-locating them gives the reader one coherent pre-Study-5 evidentiary unit that grounds the experimental manipulation. Clears Study 4 Discussion of cross-study material that does not belong there.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\claude_zero_baseline_placement.md:12:**Against:** Adds a paragraph to a preamble that is already setup-heavy. Reader sees more re-analysis before reaching the new Study 5 experimental data. The DE's R1 question response is now physically distant from the original Studies 2-4 results sections — but this is mitigated by the fact that the analysis pools those same studies and explicitly references them.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\claude_zero_baseline_placement.md:17:**Against:** Study 4B preamble is methods/setup material — a cross-study re-analysis does not belong there structurally. Awkward to tell the reader "before I show you Study 4B's results, here is a pooled re-analysis that includes Study 4B and four earlier studies." Disrupts methods → results flow. Reject.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\claude_zero_baseline_placement.md:25:**Against:** A footnote for a multi-coefficient cross-study pooled analysis with a Wald test is awkward in a Management Science paper. The analysis is too substantive for footnote-only treatment. Still does not fit Study 4B Discussion thematically. We can update the response letter to match a better placement, so the "alignment with response letter" argument carries no weight.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\claude_zero_baseline_placement.md:41:> A complementary analysis isolates the most extreme case of underrepresentation: participants whose initial selections contained zero candidates with a given focal attribute. Selecting zero of an attribute is a clear signal of underrepresentation that should provoke a response to feedback regardless of whether that attribute is race, gender, or one of the comparison attributes we test. This setup also lets us compare the response to race or gender feedback against the response to feedback about comparison attributes, holding the underrepresentation signal constant. Pooling participants across Studies 2, 3A, 3B, and 4B (Study 4A is excluded because no participant began with zero of any comparison attribute), race or gender feedback raised the probability of selecting a racial minority or woman, respectively, by 22.50 percentage points among participants whose initial selection contained zero of the focal attribute (*p* < .001, N = 864). Feedback about the comparison attributes in those same studies did not significantly shift subsequent selections among participants whose initial portfolios contained zero of the comparison attribute (effect = +7.25 percentage points, *p* = .19, N = 414). A Wald test confirms the difference between the two pooled coefficients is significant (*p* = .016). Full results appear in Appendix Section S[X]. This pattern aligns with our theorizing that descriptive feedback operates through an implicit injunctive norm against the underrepresentation of historically marginalized groups, rather than through a general response to any noticed gap in an initial portfolio.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r1_review\prior_response_letter.txt:12:We have further clarified when and why our effect appears in different settings. We re-ran our previous Study 3 (now Study 5) in order to explore the mechanisms driving how descriptive feedback about the gender of past selectees affects selection decisions when women are overrepresented versus underrepresented. When women are underrepresented, we replicate our usual effect: feedback increases the selection of women. But when women are overrepresented, the effect is significantly smaller in magnitude and reverses in direction (feedback decreases the selection of women). In exploratory analyses, we determine that when women are overrepresented and people receive feedback suggesting they have overrepresented women in a group, they are more likely to choose to add a man to the group due to fairness concerns (rather than the concerns about prejudice that we theorize propel decisions in response to feedback suggesting women or racial minorities have been underrepresented). We hope you will agree that these new data and analyses strengthen our work and offer a clearer explanation for how the phenomenon we study manifests across different candidate pool compositions. 
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r1_review\prior_response_letter.txt:30:RESPONSE: We now explicitly theorize that correction occurs when feedback about the race or gender of past selectees reveals that a person’s selections could be perceived as violating implicit injunctive norms about appropriate representation of women or racial minorities. These normative rates of selection of women or racial minorities may be different from the base rate of women or racial minorities in the selection pool – and our data suggest that evaluators’ reference point for “appropriate” representation is substantially higher than the base rate in the candidate pools for many of our studies. For example, in Studies 3A and 3B (previously Studies 1A and 1B), participants initially selected women and racial minorities at approximately the base rate (around 16-20%), yet feedback still produced large treatment effects, with participants increasing their selection of women and racial minorities by 15-20 percentage points. This suggests that selections matching low base rates are perceived as falling short of what would be considered appropriate, triggering concerns about appearing discriminatory.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r1_review\prior_response_letter.txt:43:To address this, we conducted exploratory analyses (described in more detail below, see Table R1) examining whether the effect of descriptive feedback persists even among participants whose initial selections already met or exceeded the base rate of women or racial minorities in a given candidate pool. 
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r1_review\prior_response_letter.txt:47:Notes: This table reports treatment effects among the subset of participants whose initial selections included women or racial minorities at or above the base rate present in the candidate pool. Treatment effects are reported in percentage points (pp). +p<0.1;*p<0.05;**p<0.01;***p<0.001.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r1_review\prior_response_letter.txt:49:If participants were simply using the pool base rate as their reference point, we would expect feedback to have no effect on those who had already selected women or racial minorities at or above this threshold. Instead, as Table R1 shows, we find that the effect of feedback remains consistently directionally positive and often remains significant (despite the reduced statistical power) even just among participants who selected women or racial minorities at rates exceeding the base rate. For example, in Study 3A, 75% (N=753) of participants selected racial minorities at or above the 13.3% base rate, and the effect of descriptive feedback about the racial composition of past selectees in this subpopulation on subsequent selections of racial minorities remained positive and significant (8.89 pp, p = .002). These findings suggest that participants might be comparing their selections to an internal normative benchmark that exceeds the base rate at which women and minorities were present in our candidate pools, perhaps striving for something closer to population parity (as you suggested) for representation to be perceived as “fair” representation.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r1_review\prior_response_letter.txt:50:However, as our Study 5 demonstrates, when the base rate of women in the candidate pool is high enough (75%) that women are chosen at an average rate of approximately 61%, descriptive feedback’s impact reverses direction and reduces the likelihood participants subsequently select more women. While the rate of selecting women (or URMs) in our studies is endogenous, we do present data (see Table 4 in the manuscript) showing that the effect of feedback is moderated by the proportion of women initially selected in some studies. Specifically, as this proportion increases, the positive effect of descriptive feedback on the likelihood of subsequently selecting a member of a historically disadvantaged group decreases and eventually reverses in direction. Importantly, our mediation analyses in Study 5 suggest that this pattern reflects a shift in the underlying mechanism that shifts subsequent decisions after people receive descriptive feedback about past choices. When women are underrepresented, feedback triggers a motivation to respond without prejudice, producing a large increase in the likelihood a participant subsequently selects a woman. When women are overrepresented, however, feedback instead primarily triggers fairness concerns, which produce a smaller (though still significant) effect in the opposite direction, increasing the likelihood participants subsequently select a man. This suggests that concerns about prejudice are a more potent motivator of behavior change than general fairness concerns, though both can change behavior in this context. This also helps explain why the effect of feedback attenuates and reverses as the proportion of women (or racial minorities) initially selected increases.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r1_review\prior_response_letter.txt:52:However, if pinpointing where it turns on and off feels critical to the review team, we could run studies in which we manipulate the base rates at which women (or racial minorities) appear in our candidate pools at a more granular level than we do in Study 5 to try to zoom in on the exact point at which descriptive feedback shifts from boosting the chances of selecting another woman (or racial minority) to having no effect and finally to reducing the chances of selecting another woman (or racial minority). One potential concern with this direction is that the “answer” is likely to be context dependent based on past work showing, for example, how strongly social norms in a given environment affect the number of women people aim to include in a group (see Chang et al., 2019).
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r1_review\prior_response_letter.txt:109:The results of this new study replicate those from our other experiments: when women are underrepresented in the candidate pool, providing feedback about the gender composition of initial selections significantly increases the subsequent likelihood of selecting a woman as the final panelist (from 33.3% to 57.5%, a 24.2 percentage point increase; B = 0.241, p < .001). When women are overrepresented in the pool, however, we find a smaller but still significant effect in the opposite direction: feedback decreases the selection of women (from 76.7% to 66.1%, a 10.6 percentage point decrease; B = -0.106, p = .004). A Wald test confirmed that the absolute magnitude of these treatment effects differ significantly across conditions (z = 2.50, p < .012), meaning the effect size is smaller (by 56% to be precise, though still significant) when women are overrepresented.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r1_review\prior_response_letter.txt:161:RESPONSE: Thank you for raising this important concern about organizational relevance. In response to your feedback, we conducted a new study (now Study 1) focused on an organizational setting. This study introduces a scenario that directly mirrors an actual organizational practice currently deployed by National Public Radio (NPR). In this study, participants were asked to imagine that they were a producer at NPR selecting experts to feature in upcoming stories. They were also presented with feedback on who they had covered in their (hypothetical) past stories, mirroring the types of feedback NPR employees actually see in their content management systems. Specifically, participants in our treatment condition were shown statistics about the gender composition of past featured experts alongside feedback about composition of past featured experts on other attributes NPR also tracks (age, geographic location, occupation). Participants in our control condition only saw feedback about the composition of past featured experts on attributes NPR tracks besides gender. Participants then made additional expert selections for upcoming NPR stories. Our results mirror those in our other studies: we find that providing feedback about the gender of their past expert guests motivates participants acting as hypothetical NPR producers to choose to feature more women experts in the future than providing feedback about other expert attributes (Wald tests confirmed the gender feedback effect was significantly larger than effects for age, location, or university feedback; p ≤ .01). We hope you will agree that the inclusion of this new study alongside our original Study 3 and our revised introduction more clearly situate our work in the organizational context it is intended to inform. 
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r1_review\prior_response_letter.txt:163:RESPONSE: Thank you for your comments on important potential boundary conditions of the effect we study that may arise in different organizational contexts. We join a long tradition (Aguinis & Bradley, 2014; Chatman & Flynn, 2005; Highhouse, 2009; Judd et al., 2012; Wells & Windschitl, 1999) of research that relies on varied stimuli and varied participant pools to study organizationally relevant questions, but it is certainly reasonable to question how well studies will translate from one setting to another. We believe it is a strength of our research that we present data from the field and the laboratory, with incentive-compatible and hypothetical designs, involving varied stimuli posing problems ranging from who to feature on a university campus, in a library campaign, an advertisement for the film industry, on the air for a prestigious broadcasting agency, and in an international business conference with both paid online participants and community members recruited to vote on a decision pertinent to their community. While we haven’t sampled people from every context or stimuli from every setting, the consistency of our findings gives us confidence that the effects under study are reliably large and likely to replicate in many other settings as well. We hope you will agree.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r1_review\prior_response_letter.txt:167:The results of this new study replicate those from our other experiments: when women are underrepresented in the candidate pool, providing feedback about the gender composition of initial selections significantly increases the subsequent likelihood of selecting a woman as the final panelist (from 33.3% to 57.5%, a 24.2 percentage point increase; B = 0.241, p < .001). When women are overrepresented in the pool, however, we find a smaller but still significant effect in the opposite direction: feedback decreases the selection of women (from 76.7% to 66.1%, a 10.6 percentage point decrease; B = -0.106, p = .004). A Wald test confirmed that the absolute magnitude of these treatment effects differ significantly across conditions (z = 2.50, p < .012), meaning the effect size is smaller (by 56% to be precise, though still significant) when women are overrepresented.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r1_review\prior_response_letter.txt:197:RESPONSE: Thank you for noting the need for greater precision about the type of feedback we study. We have made sure to clarify in our introduction (see p. 3) how descriptive feedback differs from other feedback interventions. More specifically, we discuss how descriptive feedback, defined as simply stating the prevalence of past selections with certain characteristics (e.g., “20% of your selections featured women protagonists”), is different from feedback containing normative or prescriptive targets. For example, descriptive feedback does not provide base rates (e.g., “compared to 40% available in the candidate pool”), peer comparisons (e.g., “others selected 35% women”), or prescriptive targets (e.g., “the goal is 50% women”).
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r1_review\prior_response_letter.txt:215:Our results from this study employing very different stimuli replicate the key findings from our previous studies (gender feedback increased women experts selected by 12.5 percentage points compared to 4.5-6.4 percentage points for age, location, or university feedback, all p’s from Wald tests comparing gender to the other attributes are p ≤ .01). We appreciate your encouragement to test for our effects with more varied stimuli and hope you will agree that the addition of this study with a very different paradigm has strengthened the robustness of our findings. 
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r1_review\prior_response_letter.txt:217:i. As you note later in Study 3, the choice sets for these studies included women/racial minorities in only 4 out of the 25 films, amounting to 16% of the films in the pool that are represented by gender or racial minorities. Does it matter if the descriptive feedback provides information about the base rates of the gender composition of the pool? That is, if I got feedback that 17% of my selection were of women, and the pool is comprised of 16% women, would that change my behavior?
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r1_review\prior_response_letter.txt:218:RESPONSE: Thank you for raising this important question about whether providing base rate information alongside descriptive feedback would change behavior. The intervention you describe—providing information about both one's own selection rate (17% women) and the base rate in the pool (16% women)—is what the social norms literature would characterize as a descriptive norm intervention or social comparison feedback (Schultz et al., 2007; Cialdini, 2003). This type of feedback has been shown to change behavior reliably across many domains, from energy conservation to health behaviors, precisely because it provides an explicit benchmark for comparison.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r1_review\prior_response_letter.txt:219:However, our research examines a different question: whether purely descriptive feedback about past selections—without any base rate comparison or normative benchmark—can influence subsequent behavior. In general, prior theorizing and empirical findings suggest that in the absence of a descriptive norm, feedback does not change behavior. We view our contribution as establishing that in fact, even in the absence of an explicit descriptive norm, feedback about DEI-related decisions can change behavior. We theorize and show that this occurs because such feedback activates the motivation to respond without prejudice. Specifically, seeing a low percentage of women or racial minorities selected acts as a signal that they may have violated implicit injunctive norms against discrimination. This triggers a corrective response driven by the desire to align one’s choices with these anti-discrimination norms, rather than simply matching the statistical availability of candidates in the pool. 
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r1_review\prior_response_letter.txt:221:ii. In short, I think the conclusion that people are more sensitive to DEI descriptive feedback to be rather broad, given the very specific type of descriptive information that is provided. I suspect in that in people’s heads, they are comparing the descriptive information to whatever proportion they believe is fair (e.g., 50% women in the gender case), rather than the 16% that is in the pool of options. If given information about the proportion represented in the pool, would people respond similarly? This seems to be an important nuance to add about the value of descriptive information, and perhaps where there could be nuanced differences even in responses between race and gender descriptive information.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r1_review\prior_response_letter.txt:222:RESPONSE: We agree with your speculation that participants likely compare the feedback they receive to an internal normative benchmark rather than to the base rate in the pool. Indeed, our data strongly support this. In Studies 3A and 3B (previously Studies 1A and 1B), participants initially selected women and racial minorities at approximately the base rate (around 16-20%), yet feedback still produced large treatment effects, with participants increasing their selection of women and racial minorities by 15-20 percentage points. This suggests that the normative benchmark participants use for “appropriate” representation is substantially higher than the base rate in the candidate pool.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r1_review\prior_response_letter.txt:224:To answer your question directly, we suspect that providing information about the proportion in the pool would attenuate the effect. Research suggests that descriptive norms exert a strong pull on behavior (Schultz et al., 2007). If participants learned that their low selection rate matched the low base rate of the pool, this external benchmark would likely serve as a justification. By confirming that their choices align with reality, this descriptive norm would compete with the implicit injunctive norm against discrimination and likely reduce the motivation to correct.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r1_review\prior_response_letter.txt:225:We theorize that this internal normative benchmark reflects concerns about violating implicit anti-discrimination norms. Even when selections match the base rate in the pool, if that base rate is low, the resulting portfolio composition may be perceived as potentially discriminatory and therefore trigger motivation to respond without prejudice. This is a conceptually distinct finding from the finding that people respond to explicit social comparison information (e.g., “others selected 35% women” or “the pool contains 40% women”), which has been studied extensively in the social norms literature (Schultz et al., 2007; Cialdini et al., 1990).
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r1_review\prior_response_letter.txt:233:The results of this new study replicate those from our other experiments: when women are underrepresented in the candidate pool, providing feedback about the gender composition of initial selections significantly increases the subsequent likelihood of selecting a woman as the final panelist (from 33.3% to 57.5%, a 24.2 percentage point increase; B = 0.241, p < .001). When women are overrepresented in the pool, however, we find a smaller but still significant effect in the opposite direction: feedback decreases the selection of women (from 76.7% to 66.1%, a 10.6 percentage point decrease; B = -0.106, p = .004). A Wald test confirmed that the absolute magnitude of these treatment effects differ significantly across conditions (z = 2.50, p < .012), meaning the effect size is smaller (by 56% to be precise, though still significant) when women are overrepresented.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\codex_brief_r2.md:121:- Study 4B Discussion footnote summarizing Table R1 / zero-initial pooled analysis.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r1_review\r1_table_section.txt:14:To operationalize “appropriate use,” we use each attribute’s base rate in the candidate pool. In each study, participants choose from a fixed pool with a known proportion of candidates having a given attribute (for example, 32% of the authors in Study 4A are racial minorities). The base rate is a neutral benchmark for proportional selection. Arguably, a participant whose initial selection rate is below the base rate has under-weighted the attribute, leaving feedback room to increase that attribute’s selection. Conversely, if a participant selects at or above the base rate, then there is no proportional gap left for feedback to close. For each of the five studies in which participants generated their own initial portfolios (Studies 2, 3A, 3B, 4A, 4B), we split the sample into Below-Pool and At/Above-Pool subgroups by attribute and re-estimated the feedback effect within each subgroup.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r1_review\r1_table_section.txt:15:As shown in Table R1, we show that even when participants’ initial selections are below the base rate, there is no subsequent increase in that attribute’s selections. More specifically, across the fifteen Below-Pool comparison-attribute coefficients, thirteen are statistically null, one is marginally positive (+9.53 percentage points, p = .07), and one is marginally negative (-16.47 percentage points, p = .07). A random-effects mini meta-analysis (Goh et al., 2016) pooling the fifteen estimates yields +0.82 percentage points (95% CI [-2.48, 4.13], z = 0.49, p = .63): comparison feedback does not move participants even when we would expect the largest effect of feedback.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r1_review\r1_table_section.txt:39:Notes: This table reports the treatment effect of each comparison-attribute feedback condition on the rate of selecting candidates with the corresponding comparison attribute in participants’ final selection(s). The fifteen rows cover three comparison attributes per study across Studies 2, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B. Estimates are OLS regressions with HC3 robust standard errors. Subgroup columns split each sample by whether the participant’s initial selections of the attribute were below the candidate-pool base rate (“Below-Pool”) or at or above the candidate-pool base rate (“At/Above-Pool”). The bottom row reports the pooled effects across studies, computed via random-effects meta-analysis weighting each study by its standard error. Studies 1 and 5 are excluded because their initial portfolios are not participant-generated in a way that defines per-participant Below-Pool or At/Above-Pool subgroups. +p<.10; *p<.05; **p<.01; ***p<.001.
