C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r1_review\response_letter.txt:36:That said, we can examine directly what happens when selections include zero of a given attribute (e.g., 0% are political leaders, 0% are women). Among participants whose initial selections contained zero of an attribute, the inference that the attribute is “missing” from the portfolio may produce some directional motivation to select one of those candidates next, in order to maintain appropriate levels. independent of any injunctive norm; if our race/gender feedback effects were driven by this inference rather than by an underlying norm, we would expect comparable feedback effects on the comparison attributes among the subset of participants who picked zero of them initially. We do not observe that. Pooling participants across Studies 2, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B in a study-by-attribute fixed-effects regression with participant-clustered standard errors, restricted to the participant-attribute observations in which the initial selection contained zero of the focal attribute, race/gender feedback increases the probability of selecting a candidate with the focal attribute by +21.28 percentage points (p < .0001, N = 1,222 across all five studies), while comparison-attribute feedback increases that probability by only +6.83 percentage points, which is not statistically distinguishable from zero (p = .21, N = 429 across six attribute-by-study cells; the remaining nine cells are omitted because the comparison attribute is common in its candidate pool and almost no participant picked zero of it initially). A Wald test of the difference between the two pooled coefficients yields +14.46 percentage points (p = .016, 95% CI [+2.70, +26.21]).
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r1_review\response_letter.txt:38:Table R1 reports each per-cell estimate together with the pooled coefficients and the Wald-test difference. The first column lists each study and its total sample size; the second column lists the focal attribute, the race or gender attribute for the study followed by each estimable comparison attribute; and the third column reports the feedback effect for that attribute, restricted to participants whose initial selection contained zero of it. The bottom three rows report the pooled race/gender feedback effect, the pooled comparison feedback effect, and the Wald-test difference between them. We acknowledge that the comparison side is estimable for only six of the fifteen comparison attribute-by-study cells, and we therefore present this as a directional, lower-powered test. The new survey described below complements this behavioral evidence by asking participants directly about the appropriateness of different attribute mixes.
