C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r1_review\response_letter.txt:58:Notes. This table reports the OLS treatment effect of receiving feedback about the focal attribute on the rate of selecting a candidate with that attribute on the participant’s final selection, restricted to participants whose initial selection contained zero of the focal attribute. Per-cell estimates use HC3 robust standard errors. The pooled rows come from a single OLS model on the stacked participant-attribute observations with study-by-attribute fixed effects and standard errors clustered by participant; the final row is a Wald test of the difference between the pooled race/gender and pooled comparison coefficients in that model. Of the fifteen comparison attribute-by-study cells, six are reported here; the remaining nine are omitted because the comparison attribute is common in its candidate pool, leaving fewer than twenty participants with zero of the attribute in their initial selection. Studies 1 and 5 are excluded because their initial portfolios are not participant-generated in a way that defines a per-participant zero-initial cell. Confidence intervals are 95%. +p < .10; *p < .05; **p < .01; ***p < .001.
