C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\cover_letter_drafts_v1.md:67:> We have addressed your two empirical requests. First, the new Study 1 importance post‑test (N = 300; one comparison attribute rated per participant) confirms that differences in perceived attribute importance cannot account for why only gender feedback moved subsequent selections: two of the three comparison attributes were rated significantly more important than the gender attribute, and the third did not differ in rated importance. Second, to address the alternative that comparison attributes are simply being selected at appropriate levels in participants' initial selections, we report a new pooled analysis (response‑letter Table R1) restricted to participants whose initial selections contained zero of the focal attribute, pooling across Studies 2, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B with participant‑clustered standard errors. Race and gender feedback raises the probability of selecting a woman or racial minority by +21.28 percentage points (p < .001, N = 1,222) in this restricted subset, while comparison‑attribute feedback raises it by only +6.83 percentage points (p = .21, N = 429); the Wald‑test difference is +14.46 pp (p = .016).
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\cover_letter_drafts_v2_codex.md:25:> We have also addressed your two empirical requests. First, the new Study 1 importance post-test (N = 300; one comparison attribute rated per participant) suggests that differences in perceived attribute importance cannot account for why only gender feedback moved subsequent selections: two of the three comparison attributes were rated significantly more important than the gender attribute, and the third did not differ significantly in rated importance. Second, to address the alternative that comparison attributes are simply being selected at appropriate levels in participants’ initial selections, we report a new pooled analysis restricted to participants whose initial selections contained zero of the focal attribute. Pooling across Studies 2, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B with participant-clustered standard errors, race and gender feedback raises the probability of selecting a woman or racial minority by +21.28 percentage points (p < .001, N = 1,222) in this restricted subset, while comparison-attribute feedback raises it by +6.83 percentage points (p = .21, N = 429). The Wald-test difference is +14.46 percentage points (p = .016).
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\cover_letter_drafts_v2_codex.md:64:- Preserved the response body’s quantitative details. The Study 1 post-test numbers (N = 300), the pooled zero-focal-attribute estimates (+21.28 percentage points, +6.83 percentage points, +14.46 percentage points), p = .016, and the subset Ns (N = 1,222 and N = 429) match the current R2 letter text.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\cover_letter_drafts_v3.md:34:> We have addressed your two empirical requests. First, the new Study 1 importance post‑test (N = 300) confirms that differences in perceived attribute importance cannot explain why only gender feedback moved subsequent selections: two of the three comparison attributes were rated significantly more important than gender, and the third did not differ. Second, to address the alternative that comparison attributes are already selected at appropriate levels initially, we restrict to participants whose initial selections contained zero of the focal attribute and report a new pooled analysis across Studies 2, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B (response‑letter Table R1). Zero is a defensible benchmark precisely because we cannot observe each participant's private notion of "appropriate": anyone whose initial selection contained zero of the focal attribute is necessarily below any plausible such benchmark. If feedback merely corrected under‑selection relative to a private benchmark, it should move participants for both race/gender and comparison attributes in this subset. Instead, only race and gender feedback does (+21.28 pp, p < .001, N = 1,222), while comparison‑attribute feedback does not (+6.83 pp, p = .21, N = 429); the Wald‑test difference is +14.46 pp (p = .016).
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\cover_letter_drafts_v3_codex.md:34:> We have addressed your two empirical requests. First, the new Study 1 importance post-test (N = 300) confirms that differences in perceived attribute importance cannot explain why only gender feedback moved subsequent selections: two of the three comparison attributes were rated significantly more important than gender, and the third did not differ. Second, to address the alternative that comparison attributes are already selected at appropriate levels initially, we restrict to participants whose initial selections contained zero of the focal attribute and report a new pooled analysis across Studies 2, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B (response-letter Table R1). Because we cannot observe each participant’s private view of the “appropriate” level for a given attribute, zero is a useful but imperfect floor that lets us hold a common starting point across focal and comparison attributes. If feedback merely corrected under-selection relative to private benchmarks, it should move participants for both race/gender and comparison attributes in this subset. Instead, race and gender feedback increases subsequent selection of the focal attribute (+21.28 pp, p < .001, N = 1,222), whereas comparison-attribute feedback does not reliably do so (+6.83 pp, p = .21, N = 429); the Wald-test difference is +14.46 pp (p = .016). We treat this analysis as imperfect but directional evidence against the alternative that participants were simply selecting comparison attributes at appropriate levels to begin with.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\cover_letter_drafts_v5_codex.md:7:> **1.** We have addressed your empirical requests. (i) The new importance post-test confirms that the comparison attributes were not rated less important than gender. (ii) The new pooled analysis shows that race and gender feedback significantly raises subsequent selection of women and racial minorities, whereas comparison-attribute feedback does not. Full details and caveats appear in our point-by-point response below.
