C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\Prereg_NPR_AttributeImportance_draft.md:25:Because a non-significant two-sided t-test alone cannot establish that two means are equivalent, we will additionally conduct three one-sided non-inferiority tests using the two one-sided tests (TOST) procedure (Schuirmann, 1987; Lakens, 2017; Lakens, Scheel, & Isager, 2018) to directly support the "equally" portion of our prediction. For each Gender-vs-comparison contrast, the null hypothesis is that the comparison attribute is rated more than 0.4 SD less important than Gender; rejecting this null (one-sided p < .05) supports the claim that the comparison attribute is at least as important as Gender within a pre-specified smallest-effect-size-of-interest (SESOI) of d = 0.4. We selected d = 0.4 because it corresponds to a difference of roughly 0.7 points on the 7-point importance scale (assuming pooled SD ≈ 1.7), the boundary of what we consider a substantively meaningful gap. With approximately 75 participants per cell, the non-inferiority test has approximately 80% power at α = .05.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\push_v8_to_gdoc.py:86:    "Second, the new pooled analysis (Table R1), restricted to participants "
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\r2_gdoc_text.txt:26:That said, we can hold the starting point constant by restricting to participants whose initial selections contained zero of the focal attribute. We cannot directly measure what each participant considers an “appropriate” level for a given attribute, but zero is a reasonable floor and is unlikely to reflect a deliberate level for most participants. In this analysis, we test the hypothesis that feedback motivates selection whenever the initial selections do not reflect appropriate levels. If that were the case, we should see feedback move participants for both race and gender and the comparison attributes in this subset. To test this hypothesis, we pooled participants across Studies 2, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B with participant-clustered standard errors, restricted to participant observations in which the initial selection contained zero of the focal attribute. We find that race and gender feedback increases the probability of selecting a woman or racial minority by +21.28 percentage points (p < .001, N = 1,222 across all five studies). Whereas, feedback about other attributes increases that probability by only +6.83 percentage points, and is not statistically significant (p = .21, N = 429). A Wald test of the difference between the two pooled coefficients yields +14.46 percentage points (p = .016, 95% CI [+2.70, +26.21]).
