C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\response_letter_gdoc_text.txt:16:To address your concern that participants might already use comparison attributes “appropriately” in their initial selections (potentially explaining why feedback about race and gender appears uniquely effective in our studies), we conducted a new pooled analysis of Studies 2, 3, and 4B restricting our analyses to participants whose initial selections contained zero books or films with a given attribute. We propose this is a conservative signal of underrepresentation that should provoke a reaction to feedback regardless of which attribute is involved. Within this sample, we (unsurprisingly) still find that feedback about the race or gender of prior selectees significantly increased the probability of subsequently selecting a racial minority or woman, respectively. However, feedback about all other attributes from our studies pooled (e.g., a film’s year of release, a protagonist’s profession) did not significantly change subsequent selections in the predicted direction if an absence of an attribute signals an “inappropriate” level of representation. A Wald test confirms the difference in the effects of feedback about zero representation on these dimensions (race/gender vs. other attributes) is significant. We describe these new analyses in more detail below and in our revised manuscript on page X.
C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\response_letter_gdoc_text.txt:44:We expect that a reputational or image concern is activated only after participants receive descriptive feedback suggesting that women and minorities have been vastly underrepresented in their past selections compared to the U.S. population. If underrepresentation of any group is responsible for our effects, then if the descriptive feedback we provided on some other selection attribute (say, the age of prior selectees) suggested a massive underrepresentation (say, of people over 50), this might drive a similar reaction. We conducted an additional analysis to try to address this possibility. Assuming that selecting zero options with a given attribute would always signal underrepresentation, we test the hypothesis that feedback shifts in who is subsequently selected to make up for underrepresentation not just when it comes to race and gender but on any dimension. To examine this hypothesis, we pooled data from Studies 2, 3A, 3B, and 4B (clustering standard errors by participant). We only retain observations involving participants who made an initial set of selections that included zero books or movies with a given attribute (e.g., a set of films in Study 3A that included zero films released after 2010, or a set of books in Study 4B that included zero books with women authors). We find that among participants who selected zero women or racial minorities initially, across these studies, receiving this feedback (that they had selected no women or racial minorities) significantly increases the probability of selecting a racial minority or woman as their final selection, respectively, by 22.50 percentage points (p < .001, N = 864). Among participants who initially selected zero movies, books, or authors with any of the other attributes under study (e.g., budget, year of release, or protagonist’s profession), feedback informing them that none of their selectees had those other attributes did not significantly alter their probability of subsequently selecting an additional movie, book, or author with the relevant attribute (b = 7.25 percentage points; p = .19, N = 414). A Wald test of the difference between the two pooled coefficients confirms that the pooled effect of feedback on subsequent choices is significantly larger when feedback is about the race or gender of initial selections than when it is about other features of initial selections (p = .016, 95% CI [+2.87, +27.63]). We have added a footnote to the General Discussion (p. X), anchored on the sentence where we first state the differential effect of race or gender feedback versus comparison-attribute feedback. The footnote summarizes the cross-study rule-out and points readers to Appendix Section S[X] for the full per-cell analysis. We hope these additional analyses sufficiently address your comment.
