C:\Users\jcerv\Jose\diversity_feedback\revision-analysis\_r2_review\zero_restriction_response_codex.md:21:In a follow-up pooled analysis reported in the response letter, we restricted the data to participant observations in which the initial selection contained zero of the focal attribute. Among participants who initially selected zero women or racial minorities, race and gender feedback increased the probability of selecting a woman or racial minority on the final selection by 21.28 percentage points (p < .001, N = 1,222). Among participants who initially selected zero individuals with the comparison attribute, comparison-attribute feedback increased final selection by 6.83 percentage points, which was not statistically significant (p = .21, N = 429). A Wald test comparing the two pooled coefficients was significant (difference = 14.46 percentage points, p = .016). This analysis is imperfect because zero may sometimes reflect a deliberate preference and the comparison-attribute subset is meaningfully underpowered, but the pattern provides suggestive evidence against the possibility that comparison-attribute feedback fails to move selections only because those attributes were already being selected at appropriate levels.
