1118:[2] We also stimulus sampled what descriptive feedback participants received about their past sources: Participants were either told that 10% (or 20%) of past experts were women, that 30% (or 50%) were under 50 years old, that 10% (or 70%) were based on the West Coast, and that 50% (or 10%) worked at a university. The effect of gender feedback did not differ significantly across stimulus sets (p = .220), and there was no main effect of stimulus set (p = .190).
1131:[15] To test whether treatment effects were equal in magnitude between the two candidate pools, we estimated separate OLS regression models predicting whether the final panelist selected was a woman, and in each model our primary predictor was an indicator for assignment to the gender feedback condition. The first model used only data from the women underrepresented condition (see Table 5, Model 1) and the second model used only data from the women overrepresented condition (see Table 5, Model 3). We then conducted a Wald test of H0: B_gender feedback (Model 1) + B_gender feedback (Model 3) = 0 to determine whether the treatment effects were equal in magnitude across the women overrepresented and women underrepresented conditions of our experiment from Study 5.
1132:[16] Studies 1 and 5 were excluded from this benchmarking analysis. In Study 1, participants did not make initial selections; they received feedback on hypothetical prior choices, making a quota rule inapplicable. In Study 5, our 2x2 design manipulated the initial candidate pool’s composition (varying whether women were underrepresented vs. overrepresented in the pool); because only half of the data from this study would be suitable for inclusion in this analysis, we have omitted Study 5 from this benchmarking exercise.
1133:[17]One alternative explanation is that feedback about other attributes shows smaller effects simply because participants are already using those attributes appropriately in their initial selections, leaving little room for feedback to move them further. To test this, we pooled data from Studies 2, 3A, 3B, and 4B and looked only at participants whose initial selections included zero films or books with a given attribute (e.g., a participant in Study 3A whose seven initial films included no films released after 2010, or a participant in Study 4B whose six initial books included no women authors). We exclude Study 4A from this analysis because no participants in that study made initial selections containing zero books with  an attribute we targeted with feedback besides the author’s race. Learning you selected zero films or books with an attribute is a signal of underrepresentation on that dimension, and if feedback's effect simply reflects a reaction to underrepresentation, it should move participants regardless of which attribute is involved. Even within the subset of our participant-feedback pairs in which participants learned they had selected no films or books with a given attribute, however, feedback that initial selections included no women or racial minorities increased the likelihood of subsequently selecting a woman or minority, respectively, significantly (by 22.50 percentage points  on average; women: +27.59 pp; racial minorities: +9.77 pp; p < .001, N = 864), whereas feedback that initial selections inSee Appendix Section B for more details on this analysis. (e.g., a big budget, a recent release year) did not significantly shift subsequent selections of books or films with that attribute  (other descriptive feedback: +7.25; p = .19, N = 414). A Wald test confirms the gap in feedback’s impact is significant (p = .016, 95% CI [+2.87, +27.63]).  See Appendix X[e] for more details on this analysis.  

