21: According to Feedback Intervention Theory, feedback most effectively regulates behavior change when paired with explicit goals, norms or targets that allow recipients to gauge their performance and direct their efforts accordingly (Kluger & DeNisi, 1996, 1998). Consistent with this prediction, Bandura and Cervone (1983) demonstrated that participants who received both explicit performance goals and feedback about their progress on a strenuous physical task exerted significantly more effort than those who received either goals alone, feedback alone, or neither; and feedback alone had no effect on effort. The effect of feedback paired with goals has been replicated repeatedly, changing behaviors ranging from energy conservation (Abrahamse et al., 2005; Becker, 1978; Karlin et al., 2015) to diet (Schembre et al., 2018; Shilts, Horowitz, & Townsend, 2004; Tate et al., 2001) and exercise (Bravata et al., 2007; Samdal et al., 2017).
22: 
23: Just as feedback accompanied by goals can motivate behavior change, past research has shown that explicitly communicating what behavior is desirable (an “injunctive norm”) alongside feedback reliably changes behavior (Allcott, 2011; Andor et al., 2020; Bhanot, 2021; Cialdini et al., 2006; Henry et al., 2019; Mertens & Schultz, 2021; Schultz et al., 2018; Tiefenbeck et al., 2018). For example, Tiefenbeck et al. (2018) demonstrated that smart shower meters displaying feedback on consumers’ water usage alongside an explicit injunctive norm to use less water, communicated via an image of a polar bear on a shrinking ice floe, reduced water usage by 22%. Similarly, Schultz et al. (2007) found that when households received feedback about their energy usage alongside an explicit injunctive norm communicating that conservation was desirable as well as a social comparison to the energy use of their neighbors, energy consumption dropped by 5.7%. However, consistent with other studies, providing consumers with energy consumption feedback alone, on average, had no effect. 
24: 
25: Altogether, a large body of research has shown that providing people with descriptive feedback about their past behavior alongside a goal, a social norm or an explicit injunctive norm motivates behavior change by letting people know both where they stand and what constitutes desirable performance. Purely descriptive feedback, in contrast, provides information absent evaluation or guidance. According to Feedback Intervention Theory, such feedback is often ineffective because it lacks a benchmark against which people can evaluate their past behavior and consider making a change (Chen et al., 2020; Itzchakov & Latham, 2018; Kluger & DeNisi, 1996, 1998; Locke & Latham, 2019). However, in this paper, we theorize and show that purely descriptive feedback reliably changes behavior when it suggests that a person’s past behavior violates pre-existing implicit injunctive norms regarding behaving in an unprejudiced manner.  Such implicit norms can be sustained by both internal motives (such as a person’s own values and desired self-image; Plant & Devine, 1998; Crandall & Eshleman, 2003) and external motives (such as the social and reputational pressures they face when others can observe their choices; Plant & Devine, 2009; Lerner & Tetlock, 1999)[a].
26: 
27: Descriptive Feedback about Diversity-Related Decisions
28: 
29: Globally,  many companies are making sustained investments to increase the representation of women and minorities in their ranks (Kirkland & Bohnet, 2017; Society for Human Resource Management [SHRM], 2022) and are eager for new tools to support their diversification goals given the potential benefits of harnessing all types of talent (Richard, 2000; Hsieh et al., 2019; cf. Jehn et al., 1999). [b]Providing regular feedback to employees about the demographics of whom they have previously chosen to spotlight, hire and promote is an approach some organizations (such as NPR, Salesforce, and the BBC) are adopting in the hopes that such feedback will spur decision makers to select more diverse candidates, but it is an open question whether purely descriptive feedback can be an effective intervention. 
30: 
31: We theorize that diversity-related descriptive feedback about selection decisions (e.g., the racial or gender composition of those selected for past opportunities) can be effective at promoting diversification in subsequent selection decisions even in the absence of an explicit goal or norm when it suggests past choices have lacked diversity. We further posit that such feedback can be more effective at influencing future choices than descriptive feedback about other features of selection decisions. Why? Because diversity-related feedback can draw attention to the potential reputational and self-image ramifications of choices even in the absence of an explicit goal. Specifically, we propose that when such feedback highlights the underrepresentation of women or racial minorities in past selections, it will raise concerns that past behavior could be seen as discriminatory and therefore risk rebuke. This is a reaction referred to as “motivation to respond without prejudice” (Plant & Devine, 1998), and it is driven by people’s desire to (1) avoid negative repercussions from others (i.e., to protect their reputation; Leary & Kowalski, 1990; Lerner & Tetlock, 1999) and (2) maintain a positive self-view or self-image (Plant & Devine, 1998, 2009; Crandall & Eshleman, 2003; Apfelbaum et al., 2008). 
32: 
33: In many societies worldwide, it is considered unacceptable to exhibit racial or gender prejudice, with legal frameworks and organizational policies supporting diversity across numerous countries (e.g., the UK Equality Act 2010; EU Council Directive 2000/43/EC; Civil Rights Act of 1964, Álvarez-Benjumea, 2023). In the United States, for example, outward expressions of prejudice are both a societally sanctioned norm violation (Álvarez-Benjumea, 2023) and a violation of the law, which prohibits acts of discrimination based on gender or race (Civil Rights Act of 1964). Similarly, in the European Union, the Racial Equality Directive explicitly prohibits racial discrimination in the labor market, codifying the region’s strong normative commitment to equal treatment regardless of racial or ethnic origin (Council Directive 2000/43/EC). This regulatory framework continues to expand internationally, with recent measures in Australia and the European Union requiring firm-level gender pay-gap reporting and setting a 40% representation target for women on company boards (Ressia, 2024; Mignano, 2024). Moreover, many organizations have explicitly committed to increasing the representation of women and racial minorities (among other groups) within their ranks (Ellis, 2025; Devine & Ash, 2022). Although the corporate posture toward DEI has fluctuated in the United States, when firms pullback from explicit DEI commitments it only reduces one source of external pressure on decision-makers to avoid selection patterns that might be judged as signaling prejudice. Anti-discrimination law, the visibility of selection decisions to colleagues, candidates, supervisors, customers, and other stakeholders, employee and stakeholder expectations, broader reputational concerns, and individuals’ own egalitarian commitments all continue to make race and gender consequential in selection contexts even if a specific employer does not foreground DEI policies (Bentley University & Gallup, 2025; Levi & Fried, 2024)[c].  
34: 
35: People’s drive to respond without prejudice can be a powerful motivator of behavior change, influencing such outcomes as their willingness to refer racial minorities for professional development opportunities (Kirgios et al., 2022) and time invested in prejudice-reducing training (Plant & Devine, 2009). More broadly, past research has demonstrated that people are motivated to conform to the implicit injunctive norms—the norms about how a person should behave—that they perceive to be prevalent in their cultures and organizations (Cialdini, Reno & Kallgren, 1990). While descriptive norms (information about what others do) can influence behavior by providing a social benchmark (Bicchieri & Xiao, 2009), injunctive norms influence behavior via the suggestion that there could be social sanctions for deviance or social rewards for compliance. In one demonstration of the power of injunctive norms’ influence on behavior, a year-long field experiment in Rwanda tested the effects of exposure to a radio soap opera portraying characters who challenged prejudicial norms. This soap opera communicated an explicit injunctive norm that prejudicial behavior was unacceptable, and it changed listeners’ behavior to be less prejudicial (Paluck, 2009).
36: 
37: We propose that when descriptive feedback reveals that an evaluator’s past selections included few women or racial minorities, even in the absence of a goal, target or explicit norm, the prevalent implicit injunctive norm that prejudice is undesirable may come to mind (Barr et al., 2018; Dovidio & Gaertner, 2004). And we theorize that this implicit injunctive norm will trigger concerns that past selection patterns could be interpreted as prejudiced, either by others or by themselves. We predict that this realization will activate motivation to respond without prejudice—prompting evaluators to adjust their behavior to avoid appearing biased, driven by both external reputational concerns and internal desires to maintain a positive self-view (Plant & Devine, 1998, 2009). In this way, we theorize that descriptive feedback about the race and gender of those who have been selected for opportunities in the past that conveys these groups have been left out will lead evaluators to adjust their behavior to make more inclusive selection decisions (i.e., selecting more women and racial minorities) in the future due to existing, implicit injunctive norms, which need not be explicitly stated in this case. In doing so, we provide evidence that sharing descriptive feedback about past selectees is a low-cost intervention that can generally be employed by managers to increase the representation of underrepresented demographic groups without relying on quotas or other illegal or heavy-handed policies that can spark backlash (Dobbin & Kalev, 2016; Leslie, 2019).
38: 
39: Summary of the Current Research
40: 
41: We present a series of experiments demonstrating that in environments where women and racial minorities are underrepresented, descriptive feedback about the gender and race of past selectees reliably motivates evaluators to increase the representation of these groups in future selections, and this effect is mediated by the motivation to respond without prejudice (see Table 1 for a summary of all studies and key results). Furthermore, we show that descriptive feedback about the race and gender of past selectees leads to larger changes in future selection decisions than descriptive feedback about other important features of past selectees (e.g., subject area expertise, experience).
42: 
43: We also show how the effect of descriptive feedback on future selection decisions shifts when historically marginalized candidates are underrepresented versus overrepresented in candidate pools. In Study 5 we show that when women are overrepresented, the effect of descriptive feedback on subsequent selections of women is significantly smaller in magnitude and reverses in direction (increasing selections of men). Further, we show that this reversed effect is mediated by general fairness concerns rather than concerns about prejudice. Altogether, these findings are consistent with the idea that feedback produces a motivation to respond without prejudice when people fear their selections signal that they have failed to be inclusive of historically oppressed groups. However, when women and racial minorities are overrepresented, descriptive feedback (communicating that these groups have been selected at a disproportionate rate) no longer signals an implicit injunctive norm violation, but it can still trigger concerns about ensuring balanced representation (Adams, 1965; Colquitt, 2001).
44: 
45: Our focus in this paper is on selection decisions, given how critical such choices are for many organizational outcomes, including who is hired and retained (Sackett & Lievens, 2008). Those hired, promoted, featured on prominent panels, selected for awards, and given the opportunity to have their work advertised receive these opportunities thanks to selection decisions made by others. Better understanding how feedback can influence such selection decisions may offer avenues for increasing the diversity of those featured in many high-profile groups (Porter & Serra, 2020, Preston & Carton, 2024). 
46: 
47: We examine how evaluators respond to feedback about portfolios (i.e., sets) of past selections rather than one-off selection decisions. Because diversity (or a lack thereof) is only a property of groups, and because an absence of diversity is more likely to be noticed in larger groups (Rai et al., 2024) and when evaluating past decisions about groups rather than individuals (Chang et al., 2020), we would expect feedback about any one, prior selection decision to be less likely to trigger concerns about a norms violation than the type of portfolio-based feedback we study. 
48: 
49: Our work relates to prior research showing that how choices are presented affects the diversity of selections. Specifically, past research has shown that when people make multiple selections simultaneously (rather than sequentially) (Simonson, 1990), evaluate candidates side-by-side (rather than separately) (Bohnet et al., 2016), and make sets of selection decisions rather than one-at-a-time selection decisions, they favor more diverse candidates (Chang et al., 2020). We hold all such presentation factors constant across conditions in all of our studies, thereby isolating the casual effect of descriptive feedback about past portfolio composition on subsequent selections. 
