70: 
71: We established across all seven experiments in this paper that in settings where women (or racial minorities) are underrepresented, providing descriptive feedback about the gender (or race) of past selectees alongside other feedback about past selectees’ characteristics increases evaluators’ subsequent likelihood of selecting women (or racial minorities). In Study 2, we established the external validity of our findings through a framed field experiment (on a university campus). To further establish that our findings are not merely driven by a demand effect, we also showed that the effect of providing descriptive feedback about the gender or race of past selectees is reliably and significantly larger than that of providing descriptive feedback about other attributes of past selectees (e.g., the fraction in a given profession, the fraction in a given birth cohort) on participants’ likelihood of selecting candidates with those other attributes (e.g., a candidate in a given profession or a given birth cohort), even when those other attributes are rated as similarly important as candidates’ demographics (Studies 1, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B). In Studies 4A and 4B, we showed that motivation to respond without prejudice mediated the effect of providing descriptive feedback about the gender (or race) of past selectees on the likelihood of subsequently selecting a woman (or racial minority) candidate. And finally, in Study 5, we showed that providing feedback about the percentage of past selectees who were women only subsequently increased the selection of women when women are underrepresented in the initial candidate pool; when women are overrepresented, the effect is significantly smaller in magnitude and reverses in direction (decreasing the selection of women), and is mediated by fairness concerns rather than concerns about prejudice.
