76: 
77: Study 1
78: 
79: 
80: 
81: 
82: 
83: In Study 1, participants imagined assuming the role of National Public Radio (NPR) producers selecting experts to interview for stories about the future of work in America. We tested the effect of providing participants with descriptive feedback about the gender composition of their previously selected expert sources on their subsequent hypothetical selections of experts for future NPR stories. This study was designed to imitate the real feedback system currently used at NPR to provide producers with summary statistics about their past sources (Fu, 2021).
84: 
85: Methods
--- lines 85-110 ---
85: Methods
86: 
87: Participants. As pre-registered (https://osf.io/vazsm/), we recruited 1,000 participants through Prolific to complete a 3-minute survey for $0.75 (55.4% women; 43.7% men; 0.9% non-binary; Mage = 43.80; 72.3% White, 13.2% Black, 6.5% Hispanic, 7.2% Asian).[1]
88: 
89: Procedure. Participants were told to imagine they worked as producers at NPR and were responsible for identifying and booking expert sources to interview for various news segments and stories. Participants were informed that for the past three months, they had been working on a series of stories about the future of work in America and had selected and interviewed a portfolio of ten experts for these stories.
90: 
91: Participants were then randomly assigned to one of two conditions: (1) the no gender feedback condition or (2) the gender feedback condition. In the no gender feedback condition, participants received descriptive feedback summarizing the percentage of experts they had selected over the past three months who (1) were under 50 years old, (2) were based on the West Coast (of the United States), and (3) worked at a university. Notably, NPR has actually tracked each of these attributes of expert sources, which were deemed a priority, and displayed them to producers. In the gender feedback condition, participants always received feedback about the percentage of past selectees who were women, presented alongside two of the three statistics presented in the no gender feedback condition drawn at random.[2] 
92: 
93: After receiving descriptive feedback about the composition of their past expert selections, participants were asked to select three experts from a list of 25 candidates for an upcoming NPR segment on how artificial intelligence is reshaping employment and were provided with each candidate's name, area of expertise, and institutional affiliation. See Materials Section: Study 1 in the Appendix for complete study materials.
94: 
95: To rule out the possibility that differences in the perceived importance of the feedback provided across conditions could account for any differential effects of feedback on subsequent selections, we ran a separate pre-registered study (https://aspredicted.org/xa7u94.pdf; N = 300 Prolific participants) comparing the rated importance of the four NPR expert attributes about which we shared feedback in our study. Each participant in this pilot test was randomly assigned to rate one attribute on a scale from 1 (“Not at all important”) to 7 (“Very important”). Compared to their gender (M = 4.28, SD = 2.33), participants rated whether experts “worked at a university” as significantly more important (M = 5.04, SD = 1.93; t(142.6) = 2.17, p = .032, d = 0.36) and “were under 50 years old” as similarly important (M = 4.49, SD = 2.17, n = 75; t(147.2) = 0.58, p = .563, d = 0.09). “Were based on the West Coast of the United States” was rated as less important than expert gender (M = 3.35, SD = 2.17; t(146.5) = 2.51, p = .013, d = 0.41). Overall, this study confirms that gender is not viewed as a uniquely important feature of NPR experts.. 
96: 
97: ------------------------------------------------------------------
