146: 
147: Results 
148: 
149: Initial selections featured women protagonists 25.2% of the time, with a slight imbalance across conditions (23.0% control vs. 27.3% treatment, p = .050). Following our pre-registration, we ran an OLS regression with robust standard errors[4] to predict whether the seventh and final biography participants selected featured a woman. Participants were significantly more likely to choose a biography featuring a woman as their seventh and final selection in the gender feedback condition (35.10% did so) than in the no gender feedback condition (21.85% chose a woman; B = 0.132, 95% CI = [0.031, 0.234], t(302) = 2.56, p = .011, see Figure 3; Table 3, Model 1).
150: 
151: As was the case in Study 1, we found no significant effects of the impact of random assignment to receive descriptive feedback about another given biography attribute in a participant’s initial portfolio of choices on subsequent selections of biographies with that same attribute (all p’s ≥ .5; see Table 3 Models 2-4). 
152: 
153: Discussion
154: 
155:         Study 2 extends our findings in two important ways. First, we find that the effect persists in a field setting where participants made consequential choices. Second, unlike Study 1, here  participants received feedback about their own prior selections rather than hypothetical decisions—confirming that the effect arises even when people reflect on their own past choices. In the next study, we test whether providing feedback about the racial composition of past selectees increases future selections of racial minorities in an incentivized experiment. 
156: 
157: Study 3
158: 
159: 
160: 
161: 
162: 
163: In Studies 3A and 3B, participants again made a real decision (akin to Study 2) and selected a set of films about famous figures from history to include in a real Facebook advertising campaign. 
164: 
165: Study 3A
166: 
167: 
168: 
169: 
170: 
--- lines 180-200 ---
180: 
181: Procedure. Participants were truthfully informed about a real Facebook campaign to advertise popular and inspirational biographical films (“biopics”) and asked to weigh in on which films to include. Participants saw25 candidate films each with a cover art thumbnail and a brief description listing the  protagonist’s name (e.g., Judy Garland, Alan Turing), claim to fame (e.g., Actress, WWII codebreaker), the film’s year of release (e.g., 2019, 2014), and budget (e.g., $10m, $14m); 4 of the25 films (16%) featured a racial minority protagonist. 
182: 
183: Participants selected a portfolio of seven films for the Facebook campaign and  were incentivized for the quality of their decisions. Specifically, we (truthfully) told participants: “To provide extra motivation to take this seriously, we’ll send you a $5 bonus if your list is selected (there will be an eventual vote on all of the lists generated).”[5] 
184: 
185: Participants were then randomly assigned to either (1) the no race feedback or (2) the race feedback condition. In the no race feedback condition, participants received descriptive feedback on the percentage of films that (1) had a budget above $40M, (2) were released after 2010, and (3) were over 2 hours long. In the race feedback condition, participants always received descriptive feedback about the percentage of films they had selected that featured a racial minority protagonist alongside two randomly drawn pieces of feedback from the list of film attributes summarized in the no race feedback condition. After receiving descriptive feedback on their initial film selections, participants selected an eighth and final film for the Facebook campaign from the original set, where their prior selections were highlighted. See Materials Section: Study 3A in the Appendix for complete study materials.
186: 
187: Results
188: 
189: Participants’ initial selections featured racial minority protagonists 16.1% of the time, with balance across conditions (p = .314, see Appendix Table S3). Following our pre-registration, we ran an OLS regression with robust standard errors to predict whether the eighth and final biopic selected featured a racial minority protagonist, using assignment to the race feedback condition as the primary predictor Participants were significantly more likely to choose a biopic featuring a racial minority protagonist in the race feedback condition (27.10% chose a biopic featuring a racial minority protagonist) than in the no race feedback condition (17.73% chose a biopic featuring a racial minority protagonist; B = 0.094, 95% CI = [0.042, 0.145], t(998) = 3.57, p < .001).The effect of assignment to the race feedback condition on the subsequent selection of a racial minority protagonist was significantly larger than the effects of assignment to receive descriptive feedback about any of the three comparison attributes (all p’s ≤ .009; see Table S3, Models 5-8 for the per-study system-of-equations results). 
190: 
191: Study 3B
192: 
193: In this study, we sought to replicate our key findings from Study 3A about how feedback affects real selection decisions, but this time we provide descriptive feedback about the gender distribution of past selectees. 
194: 
195: Methods
196: 
197: Participants. As pre-registered (https://osf.io/uyn8g/), we recruited 1,000 participants on Cloudresearch to complete a 3-minute survey for $0.75 (48.3% women; 51.0% men; Mage = 43.60; 77.9% White, 9.7% Black, 5.5% Hispanic, 6.4% Asian).
198: 
199: Procedure. The procedure in this study was nearly identical to the procedure described in Study 3A, but we changed the selection set of biopics to include 19 films featuring male protagonists and 6 featuring female protagonists (so 24% of the protagonists were women). Participants also began by selecting an initial portfolio of six films for inclusion in the Facebook advertising campaign instead of seven. The brief description provided of each film did not state the length of the film; instead, it presented information about the film protagonist’s profession (e.g., “A film about George W. Bush. Who was he? 43rd U.S. President.”). 
