C:\Users\jcerv\AppData\Local\Temp\response_letter_fresh.txt:48:I think that Study 4b goes a long way in terms of convincing me that there is something special about gender/racial etc representational feedback relative to feedback on other attributes.  One though and one request.  Although I think that the package of studies is very compelling, I still found myself wishing that you had tested whether the alternative descriptive feedback that you shared was on par with gender in terms of importance.  My intuition, for example, in Study 1 is that “(1) were under 50 years old, (2) were based on the West Coast (of the United States), and (3) worked at a university” would be seen as less important than gender.  Two suggestions -- you could get a separate group and “post-test” some of these items and if they are as important or nearly as important report that.  If on the other hand, they are a lot less important, I would ask you to consider running Study 1 again so that the paper starts with a strong study.
C:\Users\jcerv\AppData\Local\Temp\response_letter_fresh.txt:49:RESPONSE: Thank you for this suggestion. We ran the post-test you proposed and have incorporated the results into the Methods section of Study 1 (p. X). In a new pre-registered study (https://aspredicted.org/xa7u94.pdf), we recruited 300 Prolific participants and randomly assigned each to rate the importance of one of the four attributes featured in Study 1 (how many of the selected experts were women, worked at a university, were under 50 years old, or were based on the West Coast of the United States) for selecting NPR experts on a scale from 1 = “Not at all important” to 7 = “Very important.” “Worked at a university” was rated as significantly more important than gender (“were women”: M = 3.87, SD = 1.92; “worked at a university”: M = 4.50, SD = 1.48; t(139.0) = 2.26, p = .026, d = 0.37). “Were under 50 years old” did not differ significantly from gender in rated importance (M = 4.05, SD = 1.74; t(146.6) = 0.62, p = .534, d = 0.10). “Were based on the West Coast of the United States” was rated as less important than gender (M = 3.11, SD = 1.81; t(146.7) = 2.48, p = .014, d = 0.41). Two of the three comparison attributes were thus rated as at least as important as gender. These results suggest that differences in the perceived importance of the type of feedback participants receive about their selections in Study 1 are unlikely to account for why only feedback about gender moved subsequent selections.
C:\Users\jcerv\AppData\Local\Temp\manuscript_fresh.txt:46:Participants were then randomly assigned to one of two conditions: (1) the no gender feedback condition or (2) the gender feedback condition. In the no gender feedback condition, participants received descriptive feedback summarizing the percentage of experts they had selected over the past three months who (1) were under 50 years old, (2) were based on the West Coast (of the United States), and (3) worked at a university. Notably, NPR has actually tracked each of these attributes of expert sources, which were deemed a priority, and displayed them to producers. In the gender feedback condition, participants always received feedback about the percentage of past selectees who were women, presented alongside two of the three statistics presented in the no gender feedback condition drawn at random.[2] 
C:\Users\jcerv\AppData\Local\Temp\manuscript_fresh.txt:48:To rule out the possibility that differences in the perceived importance of the feedback provided across conditions could account for any differential effects of feedback on subsequent selections, we ran a separate pre-registered study (https://aspredicted.org/xa7u94.pdf; N = 300 Prolific participants) comparing the rated importance of the four NPR expert attributes about which we shared feedback in our study. Each participant in this pilot test was randomly assigned to rate one attribute on a scale from 1 (“Not at all important”) to 7 (“Very important”). Compared to their gender (M = 4.28, SD = 2.33), participants rated whether experts “worked at a university” as significantly more important (M = 5.04, SD = 1.93; t(142.6) = 2.17, p = .032, d = 0.36) and “were under 50 years old” as similarly important (M = 4.49, SD = 2.17, n = 75; t(147.2) = 0.58, p = .563, d = 0.09). “Were based on the West Coast of the United States” was rated as less important than expert gender (M = 3.35, SD = 2.17; t(146.5) = 2.51, p = .013, d = 0.41). Overall, this study confirms that gender is not viewed as a uniquely important feature of NPR experts.. 
C:\Users\jcerv\AppData\Local\Temp\manuscript_fresh.txt:55:        To formally test whether offering feedback about the percentage of past experts who were women had a larger effect on the subsequent selection of women experts than offering feedback about other attributes had on the subsequent selection of experts with those attributes, we constructed three systems of simultaneous equations (Zellner, 1962). For each system, we included a pair of equations: one modeling the effect of random assignment to receive gender feedback and one modeling the effect of random assignment to receive feedback on another expert attribute (i.e., past selectees who were under 50 years old, based on the West Coast, or worked at a university, see Table 2, Models 5-8). We then used Wald tests to compare the treatment effects estimated in the paired equations, which confirmed that the effect of assignment to the gender feedback condition on the proportion of women experts selected was significantly larger than the effects of assignment to receive descriptive feedback about the percentage of past experts who were (1) under 50 years old (F(1, 3988) = 6.63, p = .010), (2) based on the West Coast (F(1, 3988) = 8.35, p = .004), or (3) worked at a university (F(1, 3988) = 12.84, p < .001) on subsequent selections of experts with those respective attributes. This pattern of findings held across stimuli sets (see footnote 2). 
